WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.700
[Amit Varma]: Have you ever asked yourself the question, how do I look from the outside?

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:13.180
[Amit Varma]: This is actually not a great question to ask.

00:00:13.180 --> 00:00:18.020
[Amit Varma]: It can motivate us to be better people, but it can also keep us stressed out all the time.

00:00:18.020 --> 00:00:23.100
[Amit Varma]: One of the core reasons for human unhappiness is the anxiety of what other people think

00:00:23.100 --> 00:00:24.220
[Amit Varma]: of us.

00:00:24.220 --> 00:00:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Once we get past this, once we realize that no one thinks anything of us, that everyone

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:32.280
[Amit Varma]: is obsessed with themselves, that's when we can start being happy.

00:00:32.280 --> 00:00:35.120
[Amit Varma]: However, geopolitics is different.

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:36.200
[Amit Varma]: Nations aren't people.

00:00:36.200 --> 00:00:40.580
[Amit Varma]: If you're in charge of India's defense of foreign policy, then how other countries think

00:00:40.580 --> 00:00:42.920
[Amit Varma]: of us has real consequences.

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:46.560
[Amit Varma]: A resentful Pakistan may want to bleed us with a thousand cuts.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:51.000
[Amit Varma]: A strong China may want to weaken us so that we can't ever be a threat to them, knowing

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:53.120
[Amit Varma]: that we can't really fight back.

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:57.640
[Amit Varma]: In our short history as an independent nation, we have had costly conflicts with both China

00:00:57.640 --> 00:00:58.800
[Amit Varma]: and Pakistan.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:04.080
[Amit Varma]: And yes, all those conflicts were costly, even if we did win a war against Pakistan,

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:06.920
[Amit Varma]: because all conflict is a negative sum game.

00:01:06.920 --> 00:01:08.360
[Amit Varma]: Both parties lose.

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:14.360
[Amit Varma]: That is why the role of our armed forces is not just to win wars and secure our borders,

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:16.600
[Amit Varma]: but also to avoid conflict.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Our armed forces need to be strong, even if we hope like hell that we never actually have

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:22.280
[Amit Varma]: to use them.

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:25.960
[Amit Varma]: But are our armed forces equipped for wars of the 21st century?

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:29.560
[Amit Varma]: In a nuclear world, what is the relevance of conventional force?

00:01:29.560 --> 00:01:33.360
[Amit Varma]: What role can the military play in securing our place in the world?

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:36.680
[Amit Varma]: Are we up for that challenge?

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:44.520
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:45.520
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:50.880
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:50.880 --> 00:01:52.280
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:52.280 --> 00:01:56.760
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Sushant Singh, one of the finest defense and foreign policy analysts

00:01:56.760 --> 00:01:57.760
[Amit Varma]: in India.

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:02.680
[Amit Varma]: Sushant paid his dues in the trenches by serving in the army for 20 years, which included a

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:04.080
[Amit Varma]: stint in Kashmir.

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:09.120
[Amit Varma]: He then went on to become a journalist, serving as a senior editor at the Indian Express and

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:10.840
[Amit Varma]: winning multiple awards.

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:14.840
[Amit Varma]: He has taught at Yale and is now a senior fellow at the Center for Policy Research in

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:15.840
[Amit Varma]: New Delhi.

00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:20.480
[Amit Varma]: I've been meaning to pick Sushant's brain for a long time, and we finally made it happen.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:25.440
[Amit Varma]: In this episode, we discussed his time in the army, the Kashmir issue, the India-Pakistan

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:31.340
[Amit Varma]: conflict, the India-China conflict, the politicization of our armed forces, as well as the state

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:32.340
[Amit Varma]: of our military.

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:36.760
[Amit Varma]: I've done episodes on some of these subjects before with the likes of Srinath Raghavan

00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:42.640
[Amit Varma]: and General Prakash Menon, so do go over to the show notes for those links.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:48.640
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to this conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer.

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:56.400
[Amit Varma]: In fact, chances are that many of you first heard of me because of my blog India Uncut,

00:02:56.400 --> 00:03:01.240
[Amit Varma]: which was active between 2003 and 2009 and became somewhat popular at the time.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:06.280
[Amit Varma]: I love the freedom the form gave me, and I feel I was shaped by it in many ways.

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:11.200
[Amit Varma]: I exercised my writing muscle every day and was forced to think about many different things

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:13.480
[Amit Varma]: because I wrote about many different things.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:18.640
[Amit Varma]: Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons, and now it is time to revive it,

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:21.240
[Amit Varma]: only now I'm doing it through a newsletter.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:27.360
[Amit Varma]: I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com, where I will write

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:29.880
[Amit Varma]: regularly about whatever catches my fancy.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:34.500
[Amit Varma]: I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this podcast, and about much else.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:39.120
[Amit Varma]: So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe.

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:40.120
[Amit Varma]: It is free.

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:44.600
[Amit Varma]: Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:46.400
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to go anywhere.

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:48.440
[Amit Varma]: So subscribe now for free.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:52.760
[Amit Varma]: The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:53.760
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:57.040
[Amit Varma]: Sushant, welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:03:57.040 --> 00:03:58.040
[Guest]: Thank you so much, Amit.

00:03:58.040 --> 00:03:59.400
[Amit Varma]: It's a pleasure being on your show.

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:03.440
[Amit Varma]: So before we get started talking about all the areas in which you have expertise, our

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:08.040
[Amit Varma]: defence, our foreign policy, geopolitics, so on and so forth, I'm curious to know a

00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:12.600
[Amit Varma]: little bit more about you, because, you know, you've had what seems to me to be a really

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:17.660
[Amit Varma]: rich life, spent 20 years in the army, been a senior editor at the Indian Express, a much

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:21.480
[Amit Varma]: respected analyst, you write for foreign policy as well.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:25.960
[Amit Varma]: But take me to before all this, take me to your childhood, where were you born?

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:26.960
[Amit Varma]: What was your childhood like?

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:28.760
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that.

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:33.200
[Guest]: So Amit, I was actually, I belong to the state of Uttar Pradesh and my early schooling took

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:39.240
[Guest]: place in the city of Agra, the erstwhile capital of India, till the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:40.240
[Guest]: moved it.

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:41.680
[Guest]: Most people know it for the Taj Mahal.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:45.960
[Guest]: And after my graduation, I joined the Indian Military Academy and got commissioned in the

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:47.760
[Guest]: Corps of Engineers in the Indian Army.

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:48.760
[Guest]: I was a Madras sapper.

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:54.320
[Guest]: Served for 20 years in the army, which included multiple stints in the erstwhile state of

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:59.400
[Guest]: Jammu and Kashmir, including Srinagar, you know, Rajouri, Poonchheria on the line of

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:06.240
[Guest]: control, Kargil Drass sector, much later after the war, and did also did a stint as a United

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:12.120
[Guest]: Nations military observer in Cote d'Ivoire, in Ivory Coast, in West Africa.

00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:16.440
[Guest]: And there were other postings all over the country, which is usual for an army officer.

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:22.400
[Guest]: The most notable among them would be probably my stint on the India-Pakistan border during

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:26.600
[Guest]: Operation Parakram, which is the mobilization of the Indian Armed Forces after the terror

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:32.200
[Guest]: attack on Parliament in 2001, where Indian Army almost seemed prepared to go across.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:35.500
[Guest]: And a lot of activity took place at that point in time.

00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:39.600
[Guest]: After serving for 20 years in the army, I took premature retirement, voluntary retirement

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:40.600
[Guest]: from the army.

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:45.360
[Guest]: I held a corporate role for a short period of time, about a year or so, before joining

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:49.080
[Guest]: the Indian Express, where I was eventually the deputy editor, where I served for six

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:54.720
[Guest]: years, and then moved on as the as a senior fellow at Center for Policy Research with

00:05:54.720 --> 00:06:00.320
[Guest]: the Army in Delhi, besides doing some other things, as you said, still pursuing my writings

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:05.800
[Guest]: and whether it is in foreign affairs or foreign policy, or in other think tanks or other places.

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:09.280
[Guest]: That in a nutshell, is what my life has been so far about.

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:13.400
[Amit Varma]: Now, that's a fabulous nutshell to compress all of that into three minutes is something

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:17.680
[Amit Varma]: that is not permissible, and we'll unpack different parts of it as we converse.

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:20.520
[Amit Varma]: But take me back to before this, take me back to your childhood.

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:21.520
[Amit Varma]: What kind of a kid were you?

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:23.300
[Amit Varma]: What was it like growing up in Agra?

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:25.180
[Amit Varma]: Why did you want to join the army?

00:06:25.180 --> 00:06:27.240
[Amit Varma]: What were the other things that you wanted to do?

00:06:27.240 --> 00:06:28.640
[Amit Varma]: What were your influences?

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:32.880
[Amit Varma]: And also give me a sense of your pre-army life in terms of what was your day like?

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:34.120
[Amit Varma]: What kind of books did you read?

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:36.040
[Guest]: What kind of music did you like?

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:41.520
[Guest]: So you know, this is of course, I'm talking about the pre-liberalization India, pre-1991

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:44.200
[Guest]: India, pre-Babri demolition India.

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:48.360
[Guest]: It was a very different India, Agra was, it was a different world, pre-internet world.

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:52.960
[Guest]: We all, you know, I'm sure Amit, you remember those periods, that period as well.

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:58.120
[Guest]: We all went to school on time, woke up on time, went to school, slept early, woke up

00:06:58.120 --> 00:06:59.120
[Guest]: early.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:03.600
[Guest]: I grew up reading a lot of Hindi magazines, a lot of newspapers, of course, were a big

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:08.800
[Guest]: thing at that time, you know, essentially the Hardy Boys and all the other things.

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:13.760
[Guest]: And because I happened to go to an English medium school, an ICSE school, I happened

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:17.400
[Guest]: to read all the books in the syllabus, which were there starting from whether it is the

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:24.120
[Guest]: Black Beauty, to the Treasure Island, to everything that a convent educated young boy read in

00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:29.040
[Guest]: the 1980s, going up to a lot of the flies in the 12th standard, the full play of Macbeth

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:33.240
[Guest]: and Merchant of Venice and you know, 16 tales from Shakespeare, what have you, everything

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:34.240
[Guest]: the works.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:36.000
[Guest]: So essentially that is what reading was about.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.340
[Guest]: Music was primarily a lot of Hindi film music.

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:41.160
[Guest]: My mother was a Hindi music and Hindi film lover.

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:43.160
[Guest]: So we heard a lot of Hindi film music.

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:47.800
[Guest]: The English pop music came much later when I was much older in school and that was almost

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:51.680
[Guest]: at that time cassettes mainly and that was what Michael Jackson and, you know, Nothing

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:56.200
[Guest]: Gonna Change My Love For You and all the other things which we now cringe at, which would

00:07:56.200 --> 00:07:59.640
[Guest]: probably make Twitter go retro and that kind of stuff.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:00.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:01.640
[Guest]: So that was what it was like.

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:04.080
[Guest]: But Agra was a different city at that point in time and I have reflected it often.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:08.560
[Guest]: My parents still stay in Agra and I have reflected about it often that, you know, you could actually

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:11.400
[Guest]: go and see an English movies would get released there.

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:15.840
[Guest]: And I'm not talking just about 007 movies or Steven Spielberg movies, I'm talking even

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:21.480
[Guest]: about movies like the Airport 77, The Lost Horizon and very early school years, primary

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:22.480
[Guest]: school years.

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:28.000
[Guest]: I actually did go and see those kind of movies in the early 80s, including The Jungle Book.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.080
[Guest]: And I don't know if you remember, Amit, along with The Jungle Book, the India-Pakistan cricket

00:08:32.080 --> 00:08:36.600
[Guest]: series, there was an hour long film on India-Pakistan cricket series, which was shown along with

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:41.000
[Guest]: The Jungle Book at that point in time, which I remember seeing at that point in time.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:42.200
[Guest]: So yeah, it was a nice life.

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:43.440
[Guest]: It was a very different life.

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:44.840
[Guest]: It was easy paced life.

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:49.420
[Guest]: You went and played some sport, you studied hard, you know, usual middle class kid.

00:08:49.420 --> 00:08:50.840
[Guest]: My father was a doctor.

00:08:50.840 --> 00:08:55.300
[Guest]: You wanted to do well in life, the works, you know, standard things.

00:08:55.300 --> 00:09:00.080
[Guest]: The army thing came up primarily because, you know, you always are looking for a good

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:02.400
[Guest]: job and I'll be honest about it.

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:04.040
[Guest]: And also it was a very exciting career.

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:10.220
[Guest]: As a young kid, everybody loves the uniform, the razmataz and the glamour, which is associated

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:11.220
[Guest]: with it.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:13.720
[Guest]: You know, you always believe that you're going to be fighting 24 by 7 and it's all going

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:17.760
[Guest]: to be all action and glamour, which is, of course, not true as one learns a hard way

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:19.120
[Guest]: in life.

00:09:19.120 --> 00:09:22.560
[Guest]: And so essentially that is how I ended up in the army as a very young man.

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:25.240
[Guest]: I got commissioned at the age of 21 and a half.

00:09:25.240 --> 00:09:27.240
[Guest]: And yeah, and that's how the career started.

00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:30.960
[Amit Varma]: So I always kind of find this part of the conversation fascinating, especially when

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:34.440
[Amit Varma]: I'm talking to someone my own age, because it kind of makes me nostalgic because I think

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:38.360
[Amit Varma]: young people today who have the whole world at their fingertips don't realize what kind

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:40.840
[Amit Varma]: of a circumscribed world we lived in.

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:44.520
[Amit Varma]: Like all the books you named and everything, they were part of a very small set of books

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:45.520
[Amit Varma]: you're reading.

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:48.600
[Amit Varma]: If you're a kid, you're reading Annette Blyton, Hardy Boys, Nancy Drew, then you go on to

00:09:48.600 --> 00:09:51.160
[Amit Varma]: all these standard classics that you named.

00:09:51.160 --> 00:09:55.320
[Amit Varma]: Even the kind of music you listened to in college was like extremely standard, whatever

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:57.640
[Amit Varma]: you actually got cassettes of.

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:00.260
[Amit Varma]: So all of that is sort of interesting.

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:04.480
[Amit Varma]: And even in terms of careers, you know, we had so few choices open to us, humein kuch

00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:05.480
[Amit Varma]: pata hi nahi tha.

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:10.640
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, you had your typical doctor and engineering and army, of course, is another

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:15.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of option, almost seems like a separate world and people would want to do the civil

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:16.920
[Amit Varma]: services, all of that.

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:21.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm interested in another sort of aspect of what you kind of mentioned, which is that

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:24.960
[Amit Varma]: you would read a lot of Hindi magazines and newspapers.

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:30.600
[Amit Varma]: And one of the interesting sort of threads that I have, you know, explored in past episodes

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:36.080
[Amit Varma]: with people like Akshay Mukul and Rahul Verma, who you know, and, you know, Ghazala Wahab

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:41.720
[Amit Varma]: who also grew up in Agra, is, you know, whether the fact that they were reading in these languages,

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:46.600
[Amit Varma]: reading Hindi, reading something different from what the sort of the English speaking

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:51.880
[Amit Varma]: world was giving you, whether that kind of made a difference in your outlook, you know,

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:58.160
[Amit Varma]: later on in life, and I would imagine not so much with regard to your peers in the army,

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:02.800
[Amit Varma]: but many, many years down the line with maybe your peers in the media, where I'd expect

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:06.520
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, many of the people who write about foreign policy and defence and all that

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:10.960
[Amit Varma]: would be typical Latins Delhi journalists who've grown up reading and speaking and thinking

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:11.960
[Amit Varma]: in English.

00:11:11.960 --> 00:11:17.480
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that aspect of you that were you also then equally shaped

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:22.160
[Amit Varma]: by what you read in the languages, while people like me were perhaps kind of stinted, although

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:25.960
[Amit Varma]: I did study Hindi and all that in school, but were kind of stinted because we had access

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:29.840
[Amit Varma]: only to one very English kind of exposure.

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:34.280
[Guest]: Yeah, Amit, you know, I think that is to an extent true.

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:36.120
[Guest]: All of us are influenced by what we read.

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:39.640
[Guest]: If somebody probably read Tamil literature, Tamil magazines, they would probably be influenced

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:40.640
[Guest]: by that.

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:46.760
[Guest]: So if a magazine like Dharmiyog, which was regular at my regular place, or Hindi newspapers,

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:52.520
[Guest]: Jan Satta, when Prabhash Joshi was editing it, or other magazines, Hindi magazines, Hindi

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:56.880
[Guest]: articles, Hindi journals, Hindi books, whether it is Jai Shankar Prasad that you are reading

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:01.480
[Guest]: or whether it is Dharmbir Bharti's Andhayog that you are reading at that young age, you

00:12:01.480 --> 00:12:06.160
[Guest]: know, you may not make full sense of a lot of stuff and a certain sensibility and I would

00:12:06.160 --> 00:12:10.160
[Guest]: say at that time a very socialist sensibility, which pervaded Uttar Pradesh at that point

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:16.520
[Guest]: in time, UP, would definitely get through and shaped you in many ways.

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:20.520
[Guest]: It was a period of great flux and great churning, the 1980s in India, I think it's the most

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:24.920
[Guest]: turbulent decade in so many ways in India's history and to be seeing it from two different

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:30.120
[Guest]: worlds, the English world, the times of India, the Giral Jains of the world and the Prabhash

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:35.560
[Guest]: Joshi's and Dharmbir Bharti's of the world, I think the ability to see through two separate

00:12:35.560 --> 00:12:40.760
[Guest]: prisons, the same incidents, the same issues without getting polarized, without getting

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:46.840
[Guest]: into kind of the haranguing debate that we see nowadays, I think that does help shape

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:47.840
[Guest]: in some way.

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:53.880
[Guest]: It allows you to look at certain possibilities, which others may not be open to, others may

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:57.160
[Guest]: explore much later in life.

00:12:57.160 --> 00:13:02.160
[Guest]: More than that, a lot of it is late stage reflection, where we believe we read something

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:06.040
[Guest]: but we realize that we read it much later and then we transpose it to our young age

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:08.600
[Guest]: and thought that we had read it at that point in time.

00:13:08.600 --> 00:13:10.440
[Guest]: So that's equally true.

00:13:10.440 --> 00:13:15.240
[Guest]: I reread Andhayog or Rashmi Rathee and then I realized that I didn't get a bit of it when

00:13:15.240 --> 00:13:20.240
[Guest]: I was much younger or even Premchand, reading Premchand at an early age, when you are 17,

00:13:20.240 --> 00:13:24.040
[Guest]: 18, 16, you know, you really don't get what Premchand is trying to say till the time you

00:13:24.040 --> 00:13:27.440
[Guest]: understand the socio-political context in which Premchand is writing it, which comes

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:28.440
[Guest]: much later in life.

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:31.600
[Guest]: At that time, you are reading it more like a linear story, more like events happening

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:35.200
[Guest]: one after the other, more like a good novel in that sense, without realizing where it

00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:40.440
[Guest]: is situated, where it is located and what effect it does have, which I think, so the

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:44.480
[Guest]: idea that you can go back to those books again and again or maybe you could draw upon some

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:47.840
[Guest]: of those experiences does help in some way.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:52.320
[Guest]: But Amit, let me say one more thing and I'm saying this with, as somebody who's a Hindi

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:57.960
[Guest]: wala so to speak, even if I did not study in a Hindi language school, there's a slight

00:13:57.960 --> 00:14:02.960
[Guest]: amount of arrogance that has now come into a lot of people who actually studied in Hindi

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:08.480
[Guest]: or who actually were growing up in Hindi speaking households, saying that they are the only

00:14:08.480 --> 00:14:14.440
[Guest]: ones who understand the real India and I think that arrogance is something which is not correct.

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:19.960
[Guest]: It is not healthy and people should not believe that they hold a copyright over what people

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:24.560
[Guest]: would call Lutyens Delhi or people who come from different sensibilities over understanding

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:25.560
[Guest]: India.

00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:29.680
[Guest]: India is too vast and too complex a country, too diverse a country for any one of us to

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:33.040
[Guest]: claim that we understand that country or even that district.

00:14:33.040 --> 00:14:35.440
[Guest]: Districts in India are really big and states are really big.

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:39.800
[Guest]: We would not know and especially because India has changed so quickly and so fast, it is

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:45.680
[Guest]: very hard for any one of us to claim that we understand India because I grew up in XYZ

00:14:45.680 --> 00:14:50.280
[Guest]: place or I read magazines and newspapers in XYZ language.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:55.880
[Guest]: I think that's not fair on the rest of us and it shows us a kind of condescending attitude

00:14:55.880 --> 00:14:58.760
[Guest]: which at times I find very repulsive.

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:03.320
[Amit Varma]: No, that's fascinating and there's a lot to think about in what you just said and one

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:07.560
[Amit Varma]: of the points that really struck me is that meta point you made about in hindsight reflecting

00:15:07.560 --> 00:15:11.400
[Amit Varma]: and giving greater significance to something that happened in the past and we might now

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:12.400
[Amit Varma]: like.

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:16.040
[Amit Varma]: I often think that when we remember our past, when we kind of reconstruct our youth, are

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:18.080
[Amit Varma]: we also kind of making it up as we go along?

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:24.080
[Amit Varma]: I did a fascinating episode with Anshul Malhotra where we discuss kind of the nature of memory

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:28.400
[Amit Varma]: and how the brain actually works is first we remember something but the next time we

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:31.880
[Amit Varma]: remember it, we are not actually remembering the original event, we are remembering the

00:15:31.880 --> 00:15:34.440
[Amit Varma]: remembering of it and so on down the line.

00:15:34.440 --> 00:15:39.320
[Amit Varma]: It's almost as if there is a game of Chinese whispers in our head and this was like a complete

00:15:39.320 --> 00:15:45.560
[Amit Varma]: TIL for me when I first kind of came across which is why memory can be so unreliable.

00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:50.160
[Amit Varma]: I'm also sort of struck by what you said about the arrogance of people who are sort of this

00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:55.520
[Amit Varma]: almost this inverse of the snobbishness of language while earlier the people who would

00:15:55.520 --> 00:15:58.800
[Amit Varma]: study English would laud upon you and now the people who studied Hindi are saying that

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:04.040
[Amit Varma]: no only we know the real India and it actually seems to me that people who have had a multilingual

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:08.240
[Amit Varma]: a genuinely multilingual upbringing not just speaking different languages but also reading

00:16:08.240 --> 00:16:12.760
[Amit Varma]: in them and reading different papers would have different lenses with which to examine

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:19.280
[Amit Varma]: the same world and at some level I think there is a deepening there which is valuable.

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:23.560
[Amit Varma]: Each lens can also distort what you see so I wouldn't place a value judgment on it I'm

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:27.960
[Amit Varma]: sure that there are these kind of trade-offs but since we are speaking about that period

00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:33.440
[Amit Varma]: let me just kind of think aloud and take a brief digression into a something wider which

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:37.680
[Amit Varma]: is that when we look around at our discourse today like we know that the discourse around

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:43.360
[Amit Varma]: us is deeply polarized and that there is this move perhaps exacerbated by social media where

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:47.760
[Amit Varma]: everything is being pushed towards the extremes almost the opposite of the median voter theorem

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:53.280
[Amit Varma]: in a sense where our politics is being pushed to these extremes and so on and so forth.

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:59.640
[Amit Varma]: So couple of questions one is it the case that society is also as polarized as the polarization

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:04.960
[Amit Varma]: in our discourse would indicate that are we much more divided than we used to be and also

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:09.840
[Amit Varma]: my sense of Indian culture has been something that while there are these kind of strands

00:17:09.840 --> 00:17:17.080
[Amit Varma]: in it that one may not appreciate it is also very assimilative, very rich, very diverse

00:17:17.080 --> 00:17:21.600
[Amit Varma]: that cliche of a khichdi with everything in it is so accurate.

00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:25.920
[Amit Varma]: So now when you look back on say the Agra in which you grew up the people around you

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:30.040
[Amit Varma]: in those times the things that you read in the Hindi newspapers and or even the English

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:36.640
[Amit Varma]: ones what is your sense have we really changed that much as a society or does the media today

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:41.800
[Amit Varma]: and the discourse today only amplify a division that always existed.

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:49.200
[Guest]: So Amit I would say that from the Agra that I grew up in to the Agra that exists now including

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:54.880
[Guest]: some of the my closest friends in school with whom I studied and who are either now businessmen

00:17:54.880 --> 00:18:01.720
[Guest]: doctors professionals whatever they may be and probably not at my age I do find a shift

00:18:01.720 --> 00:18:06.480
[Guest]: from the kind of values that we grew up in which we all identified with at a certain

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:08.480
[Guest]: point in time.

00:18:08.480 --> 00:18:13.880
[Guest]: Is that shift as horrible as sharply divided as social media may like us to believe may

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:20.400
[Guest]: or may not be true but there has been definitely a shift which has taken place that it would

00:18:20.400 --> 00:18:24.440
[Guest]: be unfair or incorrect for us to say that no shift has taken place whether the shift

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:28.360
[Guest]: is like where no I can't talk to someone who supports a political ideology.

00:18:28.360 --> 00:18:34.080
[Guest]: I do not find conducive or healthy that's not true people my friends still talk to me

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:39.360
[Guest]: you know the old boys association still meets in that sense but are they still the same

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:45.040
[Guest]: people who would at that point in time feel very repulsed by what the Bajrang Dal was

00:18:45.040 --> 00:18:50.760
[Guest]: doing or what was going on Islamophobia that was developing in the early 90s clearly not.

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:55.480
[Guest]: So there has been a shift there has been a change but has the change been to the extent

00:18:55.480 --> 00:19:00.680
[Guest]: to where it's a clear split a very clear divide where nothing moves between the two sides

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:06.400
[Guest]: I don't think that's that's true but Agra may be a particularly different case because

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:11.240
[Guest]: Agra has always been as you know Amit a very major BJP stronghold the whole Braj region

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:16.640
[Guest]: RSS has had very strong roots owing to Mr. Vajpayee and two other leaders it saw major

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:21.760
[Guest]: riots after the demolition of Babri mosque in 1992 so it has a history it has a past

00:19:21.760 --> 00:19:27.680
[Guest]: so I know to sit on a value judgment or to or to give an answer based only on Agra and

00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:32.360
[Guest]: particularly my section of society whom I knew in Agra which is predominantly you know

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:38.680
[Guest]: upper caste affluent well-to-do people would not be fair but off the cuff if you put a

00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:43.640
[Guest]: gun to my head I would say yes things have deteriorated but are they really split wide

00:19:43.640 --> 00:19:48.520
[Amit Varma]: open which cannot be bridged may not be true you are showing your army roots by using the

00:19:48.520 --> 00:19:52.440
[Amit Varma]: expression if I put a gun to your head listen we civilians don't do that kind of thing so

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:56.880
[Guest]: okay you can maybe you know whatever you put a chemical weapon or something down my throat

00:19:56.880 --> 00:20:04.000
[Amit Varma]: or whatever yeah thereby indicating that civilians also contain much evil and I kind of wonder

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:09.080
[Amit Varma]: just to sort of take the same point forward that it's almost a cliche on my show to say

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:14.360
[Amit Varma]: that that people contain multitudes and this is something however that I've been thinking

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:19.560
[Amit Varma]: pretty seriously about recently because the truth is that all of your friends who would

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:23.620
[Amit Varma]: once have been repulsed by the Bajrang Dal but today may support that party and so on

00:20:23.620 --> 00:20:28.640
[Amit Varma]: and so forth they are not simplistic people it's not like they shifted from one point

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:33.400
[Amit Varma]: to another point there are many conflicting impulses within them and all that has happened

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:39.080
[Amit Varma]: is that perhaps one particular impulse one particular narrative strand has drawn them

00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:44.320
[Amit Varma]: out a little bit more in that direction but many of their other impulses would remain

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:49.640
[Amit Varma]: including assimilative impulses and they'll enjoy Urdu ghazals and all of that I'm quite

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:56.040
[Amit Varma]: sure so my question is that what has happened in the past 20 or 30 years is that a particular

00:20:56.040 --> 00:21:02.080
[Amit Varma]: strand of thinking about the world about thinking almost in tribal terms othering a certain

00:21:02.080 --> 00:21:06.400
[Amit Varma]: kind of people thinking about one's culture and history in a particular way there was

00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:11.520
[Amit Varma]: always a narrative within our society as Akshay Mukul's excellent book on the Gita Press shows

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:16.360
[Amit Varma]: but it has gained dominance and it strikes me that if it has gained dominance today there

00:21:16.360 --> 00:21:21.200
[Amit Varma]: is something about it that has been attractive to the people who have become attracted to

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:26.360
[Amit Varma]: it like perhaps some of your friends who have gradually changed in that way what do you

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:32.120
[Amit Varma]: think that is and do you think that there are countervailing narratives that could also

00:21:32.120 --> 00:21:36.200
[Amit Varma]: appeal to in a sense a better angels or the different angels of their nature if we are

00:21:36.200 --> 00:21:42.920
[Amit Varma]: not to put a value judgment on this particular narrative very tough to say what really triggered

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:48.240
[Guest]: those changes as you rightly said those changes have taken place over a gradually over a period

00:21:48.240 --> 00:21:53.600
[Guest]: of time till the time we see this dominant ideology at play Obama has a great line in

00:21:53.600 --> 00:21:58.560
[Guest]: his new book in the memoirs the first part you know that some leaders come and I'm paraphrasing

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:02.080
[Guest]: it you know it's not the exact thing that some leaders come they touch upon the dark

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:06.040
[Guest]: side of the of the people and the dark side comes other leaders come and they touch upon

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:09.640
[Guest]: the good side and he's actually referring to Trump in that sense you know that all the

00:22:09.640 --> 00:22:13.880
[Guest]: venom all the poison that you see comes out suddenly and all the anger comes out and as

00:22:13.880 --> 00:22:17.920
[Guest]: you rightly said maybe the narrative which had gained dominance the certain kind of insecurity

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:22.760
[Guest]: so there are multiple factors at play there's global factor of 9-11 as you probably somebody

00:22:22.760 --> 00:22:27.360
[Guest]: on your show I'm sure must by now must have explained to you how Islamophobia and anti-Islam

00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:32.560
[Guest]: thing came up and nicely fitted in with the whole thing so you know you see somebody of

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:37.040
[Guest]: my age you have the Bapri demolition the whole movement which leads to demolition of the

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:42.160
[Guest]: Bapri masjid followed at the same time simultaneously you know mixing it with the insurgency in

00:22:42.160 --> 00:22:46.920
[Guest]: Kashmir which really at one point in time people forget threatened to break apart people

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:51.040
[Guest]: really believe that Kashmir was going to break free you know most of us have forgotten what

00:22:51.040 --> 00:22:56.200
[Guest]: the situation in Kashmir in 91 92 93 was like no it's very hard for us to now imagine that

00:22:56.200 --> 00:23:02.540
[Guest]: situation and at that point in time I think that played into the whole narrative and eventually

00:23:02.540 --> 00:23:07.120
[Guest]: the political rise of a certain political force and the ideology which had always existed

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:11.800
[Guest]: in the party the decline of other political ideologies the whole mixing of it with the

00:23:11.800 --> 00:23:17.400
[Guest]: economic reform the rise of capitalism crony capitalism whatever you wish to wish to call

00:23:17.400 --> 00:23:23.720
[Guest]: it or followed by a 9-11 and the global environment around the same ideology the rise of conservatism

00:23:23.720 --> 00:23:29.680
[Guest]: art so to speak you know in a certain way all that at some level was mixing and matching

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:35.320
[Guest]: till the time it really burst out in the open around the same time mr. president Trump comes

00:23:35.320 --> 00:23:40.400
[Guest]: to power and in India the BJP comes to pass it's a journey but a lot of factors which

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:44.800
[Guest]: were happening in the background at the same time along with a dominant narrative the rise

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:49.320
[Guest]: of subaltern parties the fact that they were parties which were rising which threaten the

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:53.840
[Guest]: existing status quo whether it was the BSP the SP the Lalu Yadav of the world they were

00:23:53.840 --> 00:23:58.160
[Guest]: not really something the existing parties which were dominated by a certain sections

00:23:58.160 --> 00:24:03.000
[Guest]: of caste and class could digest so there was a lot of pushback against the chain they were

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:07.000
[Guest]: trying to change the status quo there was a lot of pushback against the status quo and

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:12.680
[Guest]: because caste system is this wonderfully graded inequality so even the middle class believed

00:24:12.680 --> 00:24:16.280
[Guest]: that there was somebody under them whom they could oppress say that they were trying to

00:24:16.280 --> 00:24:21.600
[Guest]: target them rather than trying to really go for equality as Pratap Bhanumeta's wonderful

00:24:21.600 --> 00:24:27.200
[Guest]: that thin essay book which clearly says that the idea of social justice in India was not

00:24:27.200 --> 00:24:33.200
[Guest]: about seeking equality was actually imposing your own inequality on somebody by capturing

00:24:33.200 --> 00:24:39.760
[Guest]: power so all those factors the social churn the economic churn the churn globally placed

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:44.400
[Guest]: in a context where Kashmir was happening where massive political mobilization was happening

00:24:44.400 --> 00:24:50.120
[Guest]: Mandal was happening 9-11 was happening all that came together and I think we landed up

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:54.920
[Guest]: where we landed up I would even put Kargil as part of it the fact that the militarization

00:24:54.920 --> 00:25:00.240
[Guest]: the of the Indian society the fact that hero worship of a certain kind of thinking which

00:25:00.240 --> 00:25:05.480
[Guest]: took place at the India's first televised war almost like the Gulf War in the US and

00:25:05.480 --> 00:25:11.560
[Guest]: a great comparison is how the US media covered the Vietnam War and how they covered the Gulf

00:25:11.560 --> 00:25:17.400
[Guest]: War similarly how the Indian media coverage of the military changed with Kargil is something

00:25:17.400 --> 00:25:22.060
[Guest]: which needs to be seen in this in the same context and we see more and more of that going

00:25:22.060 --> 00:25:26.240
[Amit Varma]: down the line yeah it's fascinating I mean obviously it's multifactorial and much of

00:25:26.240 --> 00:25:31.280
[Amit Varma]: what you mentioned it's stuff that I've discussed separately here though the very interesting

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:35.920
[Amit Varma]: point that I'm here that a guest has raised for the first time is how the Kargil war was

00:25:35.920 --> 00:25:41.400
[Amit Varma]: possibly our first televised confrontation in a sense and could have also played a part

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:45.280
[Amit Varma]: which is fascinating and bears thinking about I mean the interesting thing is you spoke

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:49.440
[Amit Varma]: about the rise of conservatism I would say it's a rise of the right wing per se because

00:25:49.440 --> 00:25:53.480
[Amit Varma]: Trump is pretty much an anti-conservative and even the BJP in many ways is a radical

00:25:53.480 --> 00:25:59.320
[Amit Varma]: party where they are you know seeking to uproot so much that is embedded in our society such

00:25:59.320 --> 00:26:06.200
[Amit Varma]: as our tolerance and such as our assimilative nature but that to be fair you know and if

00:26:06.200 --> 00:26:11.120
[Guest]: you go back to the to the late 80s early 90s BJP is actually not a right-wing party it's

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:16.360
[Guest]: actually a conservative party Hindu conservative party which has its origins in the Jan Sangh

00:26:16.360 --> 00:26:22.960
[Guest]: the Swatantra party and the Congress or which were all merged in in the in the Janata party

00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:27.440
[Guest]: so you have the Sikandar Bhakts of the world which are part of the BJP who came from different

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:32.640
[Guest]: strands of society so where we have landed up today maybe hardcore right-wing ideological

00:26:32.640 --> 00:26:37.760
[Guest]: project but where we came from or the journey that we took there were a lot of conservative

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:42.080
[Guest]: points which allowed it to seamlessly get through because you said you know these guys

00:26:42.080 --> 00:26:45.440
[Guest]: are slightly different you know they're not evil in that sense they're not bad guys they're

00:26:45.440 --> 00:26:49.360
[Guest]: just like slightly different they believe in a certain way of life and we should go

00:26:49.360 --> 00:26:54.800
[Guest]: with them and I think in that sense the quibble I would you know I would take a quibble with

00:26:54.800 --> 00:26:59.480
[Amit Varma]: the quibble yeah no no that's absolutely a fair point it's complex and I did a pretty

00:26:59.480 --> 00:27:04.200
[Amit Varma]: popular episode with Vinay Sitapati on this also tracing the BJP before Modi and all of

00:27:04.200 --> 00:27:08.040
[Amit Varma]: those years I mean in fact you know in the in 1980 when the BJP formed over the ruins

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:12.840
[Amit Varma]: of the Janata party it was the stated aim was Gandhi and socialism and it's really because

00:27:12.840 --> 00:27:18.040
[Amit Varma]: Congress took a move towards a certain kind of soft Hindu tour that the BJP felt compelled

00:27:18.040 --> 00:27:23.360
[Amit Varma]: to go in and kind of reclaim that ground which is very interesting and I'll link that episode

00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:27.200
[Amit Varma]: from the show notes let's get back to the narrative of your life as it were and then

00:27:27.200 --> 00:27:31.400
[Amit Varma]: you joined the army what was the army like what you expected like what attracted you

00:27:31.400 --> 00:27:37.200
[Amit Varma]: about the army as opposed to all of the other sort of options I mean one you mentioned it's

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:41.840
[Amit Varma]: a glamour and men in uniform looking supremely fit and obviously you know all of that is

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:47.160
[Amit Varma]: there but once you entered it what was army life like what did you enjoy what did you

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:51.200
[Guest]: like about it what did you not like about it in the early years the training period

00:27:51.200 --> 00:27:56.680
[Guest]: or the early years it was very enjoyable for a young man you know it opens your eyes to

00:27:56.680 --> 00:28:00.840
[Guest]: the world and as you rightly said you know I was from a pre-internet pre-liberalization

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:04.560
[Guest]: generation the army actually showed you the world in some ways you know it was a totally

00:28:04.560 --> 00:28:09.800
[Guest]: different world with the kind of it still had the a lot of traditions coming down inherited

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:13.920
[Guest]: from the British India which looked very glamorous at that point in time and very fascinating

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:19.000
[Guest]: and you know so much of discipline so much of clarity very structured regimented way

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:23.920
[Guest]: of thinking all that men are physically fit no bloody civilians you know what do they

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:29.760
[Guest]: know kind of you know if you are 21 22 year old it can be very you know intoxicating it

00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:33.280
[Guest]: can really get to your head you'll say well guys we are superior to you know so the whole

00:28:33.280 --> 00:28:37.000
[Guest]: idea in the military at that point in time you're superior to all these bloody people

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:40.840
[Guest]: you know these guys are lesser inferior human beings because you are disciplined because

00:28:40.840 --> 00:28:44.640
[Guest]: you can run you know whatever 16 kilometers and this thing you can run 5 kilometers with

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:49.360
[Guest]: so much of weight in 20 minutes because you can walk straight talk straight look straight

00:28:49.360 --> 00:28:52.960
[Guest]: and you can drill smartly you know you guys are superior human beings and so you know

00:28:52.960 --> 00:28:58.240
[Guest]: and for any human being especially a 20 22 23 year old guy it's very easy to believe

00:28:58.240 --> 00:29:01.200
[Guest]: that he's superior to others you know we in any case all of us believe you believe it

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:05.000
[Guest]: even now I believe it and now that I'm so at that point in time it just gets to your

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:09.200
[Guest]: head so that's wonderful so you are completely intoxicated and you love it and you know that

00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:13.320
[Guest]: you love the fact that all this is happening a lot of people get disillusioned as young

00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:17.720
[Guest]: army officers when they are posted to P stations because in P stations you are doing some bit

00:29:17.720 --> 00:29:22.000
[Guest]: of training you are doing a lot of routine administration it's a very boring thankless

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:27.280
[Guest]: kind of job it is not that challenging fortunately I was lucky I landed up in Kashmir I landed

00:29:27.280 --> 00:29:31.960
[Guest]: up in Srinagar early on for three years and Srinagar at that point of time was the peak

00:29:31.960 --> 00:29:35.760
[Guest]: of militancy you know I was a place called Hafchanar it used to be the old Jekyll Eye

00:29:35.760 --> 00:29:41.640
[Guest]: Center and it was the peak of militancy and as a sapper officer you a young sapper officer

00:29:41.640 --> 00:29:47.160
[Guest]: you would go with various patrols you would diffuse IEDs you would make bridges you would

00:29:47.160 --> 00:29:52.360
[Guest]: do all the other things dealing with explosives so it was a challenging time and very it felt

00:29:52.360 --> 00:29:57.280
[Guest]: good so you were experiencing what really you one doesn't realize at that point in time

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:01.680
[Guest]: that one would never experience again in the military actually so I had to straight away

00:30:01.680 --> 00:30:07.040
[Guest]: go there was pretty enjoyable pretty heady in a way and almost kind of validated the

00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:12.040
[Guest]: decision to join the army it is as you grow in service as you do more more peace postings

00:30:12.040 --> 00:30:16.840
[Guest]: as you you know go through routine administrative duties as you realize that it is like any

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:21.040
[Guest]: other organization any other bureaucracy any with all these internal politics everything

00:30:21.040 --> 00:30:26.200
[Guest]: etc then you slowly realize that this is a different and you also grow up you also reflect

00:30:26.200 --> 00:30:31.360
[Guest]: back at reflect at things look at things and that is how one traverses the journey but

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:35.800
[Guest]: for me the early years at least the first five six years of my service were really wonderful

00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:41.560
[Guest]: were really enjoyable and they in some sense they are still remain a marker in my life

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:44.920
[Guest]: but but when you talk about the military or the military training there is a great phrase

00:30:44.920 --> 00:30:51.080
[Guest]: in Juswan Singh's memoirs about military training and I actually admired it when I read it because

00:30:51.080 --> 00:30:55.240
[Guest]: if some and he was saying that he thought about this when he was 16 he was in the National

00:30:55.240 --> 00:30:59.200
[Guest]: Defense Academy and if somebody could think about that at 16 while he was undergoing military

00:30:59.200 --> 00:31:03.440
[Guest]: training after coming from Mayo that it actually breaks you down military training breaks you

00:31:03.440 --> 00:31:08.880
[Guest]: down and tries to fit you in a pattern and I try to resist breaking down without being

00:31:08.880 --> 00:31:13.360
[Guest]: pointed out he said in my head I decided I would not break down and would not form part

00:31:13.360 --> 00:31:18.000
[Guest]: of this pack and I thought if somebody could actually think that at 16 and do it it's amazing

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:21.160
[Guest]: you know most people do not even realize that they are being broken down in the name of

00:31:21.160 --> 00:31:25.680
[Guest]: discipline in the name of motivation and we try to fit into a pattern for Juswan Singh

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:29.640
[Guest]: to realize it and that's why he decided to quit the army very early a failed and then

00:31:29.640 --> 00:31:34.680
[Guest]: again went on to quit the army much later it's a great couple of pages in his memoir

00:31:34.680 --> 00:31:41.000
[Guest]: something called a matter of honor the memoirs I thought that was a very apt description

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:46.400
[Guest]: but for lesser mortals like us very difficult to ascertain at an early stage in life it

00:31:46.400 --> 00:31:50.160
[Guest]: takes much longer to realize the bit of truth in that it may not be the full truth but it

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:54.640
[Amit Varma]: contains a lot of truth that statement from Juswan Singh no that is in fact a staggering

00:31:54.640 --> 00:31:59.360
[Amit Varma]: bit of self-awareness like not just for someone aged 16 but anyone I mean that kind of self-awareness

00:31:59.360 --> 00:32:03.880
[Amit Varma]: where you can look at yourself and what's happening to you like that is pretty rare

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:07.640
[Amit Varma]: so you know a smaller question and a broader question and the smaller question is not so

00:32:07.640 --> 00:32:11.780
[Amit Varma]: much smaller really but it pertains only to you therefore but it's a large question pertaining

00:32:11.780 --> 00:32:16.000
[Amit Varma]: to you which is that Juswan Singh self-awareness and obviously not everybody can have that

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:22.160
[Amit Varma]: and all of that but what is your image of yourself developing through this entire period

00:32:22.160 --> 00:32:25.040
[Amit Varma]: like of course you're a young man you get into the army you've pointed out you know

00:32:25.040 --> 00:32:30.120
[Amit Varma]: all the seductions of it you know you're fit you're fitter than everyone you're probably

00:32:30.120 --> 00:32:34.120
[Amit Varma]: you think you're smarter than everyone because you are being taught stuff within the army

00:32:34.120 --> 00:32:39.680
[Amit Varma]: and all of those things are there but how is your self-image then evolving over a period

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:46.240
[Amit Varma]: of time like how does Sushant Singh see himself at 18 and 22 and 26 and 30 and how is that

00:32:46.240 --> 00:32:52.400
[Guest]: kind of progressing over time it's a tough question to answer but I think at 22 23 the

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:56.840
[Guest]: self-reflection is more about that I'm doing a great job I'm doing a wonderful job and

00:32:56.840 --> 00:33:00.360
[Guest]: perhaps I'm doing national service you know I'm doing something which I'm trained for

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:05.880
[Guest]: and I'm enjoying myself by age 30 and I'm now just trying to calculate where I was when

00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:13.680
[Guest]: I was when I was age when I was age 30 by age 30 it is you know you really as you go

00:33:13.680 --> 00:33:18.560
[Guest]: up the slightly up the hierarchy you become more aware of the career you know the advanced

00:33:18.560 --> 00:33:22.680
[Guest]: career advancements the promotions the courses the routine administrative things and other

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:26.720
[Guest]: bureaucratic norms which are there you know you also move along in your family life you

00:33:26.720 --> 00:33:30.160
[Guest]: probably get married you may or may not have kids or you are on your way to having kids

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:34.440
[Guest]: etc and that brings a different dimension to the whole life you know people expect you

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:39.080
[Guest]: to be more responsible your bosses which is which they don't expect you to 22 at 22 you

00:33:39.080 --> 00:33:42.440
[Guest]: can be really brash you know and people will say oh he's a young man so you know god he's

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:47.560
[Guest]: got a lot of josh as they call it in the army so all those things happen at in the journey

00:33:47.560 --> 00:33:52.640
[Guest]: yeah more self-awareness more self-reflection starts coming in and you start looking at

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:56.280
[Guest]: the world you start looking at the world outside by that time you know when you are when you

00:33:56.280 --> 00:34:00.000
[Guest]: are 21 22 you are probably among the earliest lot of your friends who have settled down

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:05.000
[Guest]: in life and earning a salary and you know having a good job by the time you're 30 most

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.960
[Guest]: of your friends have settled down they're earning they're also living a life so you

00:34:07.960 --> 00:34:12.400
[Guest]: are able to even if you don't want to almost compare with others and look at others and

00:34:12.400 --> 00:34:16.760
[Guest]: see how they are doing by that time they're also settling down how their life is and then

00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:20.600
[Guest]: you start reflecting on what could have gone better for them what could have gone better

00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:24.280
[Guest]: for you yeah that is a time when you start looking at yourself differently you've done

00:34:24.280 --> 00:34:28.440
[Guest]: a couple of peace postings courses etc you start wanting to do well in your career all

00:34:28.440 --> 00:34:33.880
[Amit Varma]: those things take place at that point in time so and at this point i'd also sort of like

00:34:33.880 --> 00:34:38.360
[Amit Varma]: to ask you about like i find it interesting that you were sort of into separate bubbles

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:42.280
[Amit Varma]: at two different points in time one of which you already mentioned it's the army bubble

00:34:42.280 --> 00:34:46.360
[Amit Varma]: where you know people within the army will look at themselves as different from the civilians

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:50.680
[Amit Varma]: and perhaps a little superior but the other interesting bubble is the bubble which you

00:34:50.680 --> 00:34:56.440
[Amit Varma]: are in when you are in kashmir kashmiri people are you know one thing and you are in a bubble

00:34:56.440 --> 00:35:03.320
[Amit Varma]: of your own as somebody from india from mainland india somebody who is in the army and in a

00:35:03.320 --> 00:35:09.040
[Amit Varma]: sense there is at some level surely some sense where the local people look upon you with

00:35:09.040 --> 00:35:14.380
[Amit Varma]: hostility as if you are oppressors you are kind of an other for them what was that sort

00:35:14.380 --> 00:35:19.640
[Amit Varma]: of period alike like what if like first of all for a person in the army in kashmir at

00:35:19.640 --> 00:35:25.160
[Amit Varma]: that point what is your approach towards the local population what is their approach towards

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:31.040
[Amit Varma]: you and how does that thinking kind of deepen as the years go by yeah so the period that

00:35:31.040 --> 00:35:37.680
[Guest]: i'm talking about that we are discussing is early 90s and at that point in time the the

00:35:37.680 --> 00:35:41.920
[Guest]: situation was very tense in kashmir and the army was really trying to regain control in

00:35:41.920 --> 00:35:46.440
[Guest]: some ways there was no civilian government in place in kashmir and things had been very

00:35:46.440 --> 00:35:52.440
[Guest]: very bad a lot of army units a lot of paramilitary forces had been had been pushed inside the

00:35:52.440 --> 00:35:57.760
[Guest]: pushed inside the valley there was a of course a lot of hostility from the kashmiris towards

00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:02.080
[Guest]: the security forces but the power equation was clear the power was with the security

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:07.840
[Guest]: forces who were trying to establish some kind of order some kind of you know state power

00:36:07.840 --> 00:36:13.840
[Guest]: in the leave the stamp of state power at that point in time trying to deal both with the

00:36:13.840 --> 00:36:18.760
[Guest]: militancy or the armed militancy that was support being supported by the pakistan while

00:36:18.760 --> 00:36:23.280
[Guest]: also trying to find a way to deal with the civilian population this is the period in

00:36:23.280 --> 00:36:27.060
[Guest]: kashmir where it is more about dealing with the armed militancy and regaining some kind

00:36:27.060 --> 00:36:32.560
[Guest]: of control over the over the violence in the in the kashmir valley and there was of course

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:38.560
[Guest]: as i said a lot of hostility which one could see and people the are the soldiers the officers

00:36:38.560 --> 00:36:44.000
[Guest]: a lot of them were dying a lot of them were losing their lives a lot of militants were

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:49.920
[Guest]: coming in from well trained from pakistan many others were coming who had fought in

00:36:49.920 --> 00:36:55.200
[Guest]: afghanistan and the after against the soviet union and had been freed after the war got

00:36:55.200 --> 00:37:00.160
[Guest]: over and all were fighting with the taliban or the forces and were coming back well trained

00:37:00.160 --> 00:37:04.120
[Guest]: it was a very tough period indian army was itself learning how to deal with this kind

00:37:04.120 --> 00:37:08.360
[Guest]: of counter-insurgency amit as you know indian army had only dealt with counter-insurgency

00:37:08.360 --> 00:37:12.680
[Guest]: in nagaland before that or in sri lanka and sri lanka was a totally different kind of

00:37:12.680 --> 00:37:18.160
[Guest]: experience against the ltd a lot of lessons which were learned from the ltd could not

00:37:18.160 --> 00:37:23.400
[Guest]: be actually you know used against these militant these militants who were trained in a in a

00:37:23.400 --> 00:37:27.640
[Guest]: totally different frame and were using completely different things to give you an example the

00:37:27.640 --> 00:37:34.720
[Guest]: kind of ieds or the improvised explosive devices that the ltd used were more like vietnam in

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:39.160
[Guest]: that sense you know bamboo sticks you know all those deceptive deceptive kind of things

00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:44.040
[Guest]: but what you saw here was far more technologically advanced electronics almost like with remote

00:37:44.040 --> 00:37:48.400
[Guest]: control ids and all those other kind of things pressure switches but things which were far

00:37:48.400 --> 00:37:52.080
[Guest]: more sophisticated or different the tactics were different these were far more battle-hardened

00:37:52.080 --> 00:37:56.120
[Guest]: people they had better weaponry in that sense and the indian army as you know and the indian

00:37:56.120 --> 00:38:03.480
[Guest]: armed forces since the time of 1950s in nagaland do not use air power do not use heavy weaponry

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:07.640
[Guest]: when i say heavy weaponry they do not use mortars they do not use artillery against

00:38:07.640 --> 00:38:13.400
[Guest]: any of the armed militancy the very rare example is the manipur thing in the late 1960s where

00:38:13.400 --> 00:38:19.560
[Guest]: air power was used so that actually you know makes it almost if i may say a battle of equals

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:25.080
[Guest]: so to speak that he also the militant also has an ak-47 i also have an ak-47 who is better

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:28.440
[Guest]: with the weapon will win but it is not like a duel in that sense it's of course there

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:32.200
[Guest]: are more things in the numbers the understanding of the terrain the local support all those

00:38:32.200 --> 00:38:37.680
[Guest]: factors come into play so it was a very tough period the sympathy for the local population

00:38:37.680 --> 00:38:42.680
[Guest]: was limited at that point in time as the target was militancy and suppressing the violence

00:38:42.680 --> 00:38:48.260
[Guest]: so that is how it was at that point in time and the whole idea was about wresting back

00:38:48.260 --> 00:38:55.360
[Guest]: control of kashmir and to ensure that it is that it remains a part of india and the sovereignty

00:38:55.360 --> 00:39:00.800
[Guest]: of the indian state is not is not harmed a lot of it was directed towards that i wrote

00:39:00.800 --> 00:39:07.640
[Amit Varma]: a column a few years ago which was about sort of how the situation in kashmir kind of evolved

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:12.640
[Amit Varma]: and one of the things i wrote about in that was exactly what you said about counterinsurgency

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:16.560
[Amit Varma]: which you know till in fact the iraq war even the americans really hadn't figured it out

00:39:16.560 --> 00:39:22.160
[Amit Varma]: david galula wrote a famous book a few decades ago called counterinsurgency warfare theory

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:27.080
[Amit Varma]: and practice and one of the early practitioners of this kind of warfare was in fact mao one

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:34.400
[Amit Varma]: of mao's generals defined counterinsurgency as quote 20 military action and 80 political

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:39.640
[Amit Varma]: and te lawrence and seven pillars of wisdom once spoke about how quote war upon rebellion

00:39:39.640 --> 00:39:44.000
[Amit Varma]: was messy and slow like eating soup with a knife stop quote and and eating soup with

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:49.280
[Amit Varma]: a knife in fact seems a very sort of a vivid description of what it would have felt like

00:39:49.280 --> 00:39:53.200
[Amit Varma]: and one of the points that they kind of made and there's a great book by fred kaplan called

00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:58.900
[Amit Varma]: i think the insurgents about the insurgents within the american army including david petraeus

00:39:58.900 --> 00:40:04.160
[Amit Varma]: who tried to sort of bring this new wisdom to the fore after the iraq war went downhill

00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:09.400
[Amit Varma]: but talk about again go back to the 20 military 80 political part and say that what an army

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:14.920
[Amit Varma]: must do in any situation of such insurgency is what they call clear build hold that first

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:19.240
[Amit Varma]: you clear the ground of all the terrorists who are coming from outside and then you kind

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:26.240
[Amit Varma]: of consolidate there and all of that and a lot of it involves getting the local population

00:40:26.240 --> 00:40:30.960
[Amit Varma]: to your side and this seems to me to have been a spectacular failure of the indian army

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:37.060
[Amit Varma]: in kashmir that essentially the indian administration there i won't just say the army alienated

00:40:37.060 --> 00:40:44.040
[Amit Varma]: local kashmiris and a lot of that just happened uh the way the incentives went down for example

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:49.120
[Amit Varma]: david devadas wrote a book called the generation of rage in kashmir where at one point he talks

00:40:49.120 --> 00:40:54.840
[Amit Varma]: about how uh you know the number of kills the number of terrorists killed became a metric

00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:59.840
[Amit Varma]: for the advancement of the forces so he speaks about how court officers and units sometimes

00:40:59.840 --> 00:41:04.360
[Amit Varma]: competed to notch up higher numbers stop court he talks about how there was a bump him off

00:41:04.360 --> 00:41:09.560
[Amit Varma]: culture suspects were routinely killed in encounters he gives cases where innocent people

00:41:09.560 --> 00:41:14.380
[Amit Varma]: are taken from one area to the other killed past of a terrorist to get rewards and this

00:41:14.380 --> 00:41:19.560
[Amit Varma]: kind of continues like devdas for example there's one para from his book which i'd quoted

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:23.640
[Amit Varma]: in my column which struck me as striking where he writes quote waheed para experienced this

00:41:23.640 --> 00:41:29.480
[Amit Varma]: in 2005 when he was in his late teens a bsf officer accused him of being a militant dramatically

00:41:29.480 --> 00:41:34.160
[Amit Varma]: holding a pistol to his head and then tortured him mentally until he broke down he was released

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:38.640
[Amit Varma]: after a minister in the state government intervened but the swaggering officer threatened while

00:41:38.640 --> 00:41:42.960
[Amit Varma]: letting him go that he would discover weapons from the car and then blow up that car with

00:41:42.960 --> 00:41:47.240
[Amit Varma]: the boy in it the boy was studying in class 11 when he became a victim of such torture

00:41:47.240 --> 00:41:52.320
[Amit Varma]: and threats the reason was greed that officer wanted the boy's new black indigo car stop

00:41:52.320 --> 00:41:56.320
[Amit Varma]: court and there was a das's overall point is that the situation in kashmir was actually

00:41:56.320 --> 00:42:01.200
[Amit Varma]: becoming much better you know during the time vajpayee had his talks with nawaz sharif and

00:42:01.200 --> 00:42:06.040
[Amit Varma]: you know in the middle of the auties but it suddenly became much worse because the administration

00:42:06.040 --> 00:42:11.640
[Amit Varma]: just kept treating the locals in a sense of way the british treated us if not far worse

00:42:11.640 --> 00:42:16.360
[Amit Varma]: looking back in that period with you know perhaps a lot of the wisdom you have in hindsight

00:42:16.360 --> 00:42:21.760
[Amit Varma]: as well would you say that the indian army made big mistakes there in the 1990s and if

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:28.120
[Guest]: so what were they so uh i made a very long question and very tough question to answer

00:42:28.120 --> 00:42:33.000
[Guest]: for a former army man but let me put this the insurgency and the counter-insurgency

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:38.640
[Guest]: in kashmir at least what i have understood the way i look at it is actually divided into

00:42:38.640 --> 00:42:44.720
[Guest]: few you know parts one is the period between 89 and 96 and of course there are multiple

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:50.680
[Guest]: parts to it the early part is jklf led and then the jklf declines jklf is the urban local

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:55.880
[Guest]: you know kashmiri azadi kind of a group which is replaced by a more pro-pakistan uh his

00:42:55.880 --> 00:43:00.120
[Guest]: bill mujahideen which actually you know suppresses the jklf and almost finished the jklf at that

00:43:00.120 --> 00:43:05.560
[Guest]: point in time then comes the period of the suicide bombers the suicide attackers the fedayeen

00:43:05.560 --> 00:43:10.120
[Guest]: who start attacking and this is all happening within the 90s until 96 and i put 96 as a

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:15.840
[Guest]: marker because of the elections that took place which were supposedly successful both

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:19.800
[Guest]: the lok sabha as well as the assembly elections assembly elections brought the farooq abdullah

00:43:19.800 --> 00:43:25.120
[Guest]: government to government to power and uh around that same time you have the counter-insurgents

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:29.960
[Guest]: the kokapare and the and the others who were propped up by the state to fight against the

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:34.800
[Guest]: insurgency the whole endeavor at that point in time in this period when you look from

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:40.200
[Guest]: the angle of the state indian state at that point in time was somehow get control of the

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:45.520
[Guest]: situation and the only thing that the metric or the metric for can bringing the control

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:51.280
[Guest]: was can i suppress the violence and i know for a fact that the idea manoj joshi probably

00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:58.200
[Guest]: has quoted in his book on kashmir about that period is very clear that the why is the local

00:43:58.200 --> 00:44:03.440
[Guest]: afraid of the militant and not afraid of the army we may in hindsight look at it wrongly

00:44:03.440 --> 00:44:09.120
[Guest]: but try to think of an institution a state an organization under tremendous pressure

00:44:09.120 --> 00:44:14.840
[Guest]: and almost an instrument of last resort believing that things were slipping away and trying

00:44:14.840 --> 00:44:21.440
[Guest]: to regain control that was the mindset with which that period was approached till 96.

00:44:21.440 --> 00:44:26.240
[Guest]: so in 1996 farooq abdullah comes to power with a huge majority and i think there is

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:30.280
[Guest]: a shift that takes place in kashmir around that time and i'm not going to say the shift

00:44:30.280 --> 00:44:35.840
[Guest]: is radical in some way but there is some semblance of democracy at that point in time the army's

00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:41.000
[Guest]: behavior the other not army only the whole behavior of the security forces changes and

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:45.640
[Guest]: i saw this with my own eyes even in a place like srinagar the behavior changes you know

00:44:45.640 --> 00:44:50.440
[Guest]: people could walk up to their local mla etc who could come if there was something wrong

00:44:50.440 --> 00:44:55.600
[Guest]: or something which was harsh being done by the security forces and could represent even

00:44:55.600 --> 00:44:59.840
[Guest]: a semblance of democracy could actually allow that to happen in kashmir at that point in

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:08.720
[Guest]: time from 96 till almost 2003 2003 is when the ceasefire takes place on the line of control

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:12.400
[Guest]: and this is the peak of the vashpayee musharraf engagement you know this is really the high

00:45:12.400 --> 00:45:18.560
[Guest]: point of that engagement is a totally different phase of insurgency where actually violence

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:26.240
[Guest]: does not come down but army the security forces response becomes less harsher now you know

00:45:26.240 --> 00:45:29.600
[Guest]: i'm not going to argue with you and say oh everything was fine everything was hunky-dory

00:45:29.600 --> 00:45:33.360
[Guest]: and you know we were like completely following everything in the court but you know but this

00:45:33.360 --> 00:45:37.840
[Guest]: is the period when the chiefs of army staffs commandments are told to everyone people are

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:42.000
[Guest]: actually sent behind bars people are punished through court marshals for any excesses people

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:46.160
[Guest]: are being held to account in whatever manner that they were being held to account whether

00:45:46.160 --> 00:45:49.920
[Guest]: through the channels of the military or through other channels of the of the state and this

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:55.120
[Guest]: is a time when violence actually does not go down in 2001 if i'm not wrong is the peak

00:45:55.120 --> 00:45:59.760
[Guest]: of militancy in kashmir in terms of fatality at some three thousand four thousand people

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:07.280
[Guest]: died in kashmir in 2001 from 2003 when the ceasefire takes place and 2001 is actually

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:11.200
[Guest]: when Musharraf goes on television and says they know that we will stop all militant training

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:16.480
[Guest]: we will do everything etc etc 2001 2002 and by 2003 you have the ceasefire the militancy

00:46:16.480 --> 00:46:22.640
[Guest]: suddenly comes down and by 2012 we have what 100 odd people dead and i think 2012 is the

00:46:22.640 --> 00:46:28.000
[Guest]: lowest in militancy and then it again it's a secular decline almost like 400 odds 300

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:34.160
[Guest]: or 200 or 100 odd like it's like and the 2012 if i'm not wrong was a period when less people

00:46:34.160 --> 00:46:40.000
[Guest]: died in kashmir then they died before 89 and you know normal robberies etc whatever violence

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:44.640
[Guest]: you would have in the on these streets and towards 2012 there's a rise which really

00:46:44.640 --> 00:46:51.280
[Guest]: shoots through the roof post 2015 and 2016 burhanwani so in the whole thing however put

00:46:51.280 --> 00:46:56.240
[Guest]: it is you know 89 to 96 more desperate phase you know when you're trying to regain some

00:46:56.240 --> 00:47:02.480
[Guest]: amount of control 96 to 2003 you know most stable kind of you know more trying to find

00:47:02.480 --> 00:47:06.560
[Guest]: a balance between how to use the strong arm as well as trying to win the hearts and minds

00:47:06.560 --> 00:47:10.160
[Guest]: so to speak but there's a contestation that is going on it's not a perfect thing but it's

00:47:10.160 --> 00:47:16.160
[Guest]: a contestation that is going on and then from 2003 there's a militancy is coming down muftis

00:47:16.160 --> 00:47:20.480
[Guest]: forms a government in pdp forms a government with congress and then omar comes to power

00:47:20.480 --> 00:47:26.160
[Guest]: with congress the state governments is asserting their power they're part of this whole structure

00:47:26.160 --> 00:47:30.080
[Guest]: which is created in in srinagar and jammu where they head the committees which have

00:47:30.080 --> 00:47:36.160
[Guest]: the military within it and from 2003 to 2014-15 is a totally different phase of militancy in

00:47:36.160 --> 00:47:43.600
[Guest]: kashmir and it is around 2015-2016 that militancy and now this time more local than supported by

00:47:43.600 --> 00:47:49.360
[Guest]: pakistan really shoots through the roof so i mean i don't know if you are aware but this year so far

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:54.160
[Guest]: every single militant who has been killed in kashmir valley is a local there is no foreign

00:47:54.160 --> 00:47:59.200
[Guest]: militant yeah this is stunning data you know we have i don't think in the last 30 years we have

00:47:59.200 --> 00:48:03.360
[Guest]: ever had a year where there was no foreign militant killed so if it continues i don't know whether it

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:08.560
[Guest]: will continue or not but till a few days back no foreign militant had been killed and that is the

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:14.720
[Guest]: phase in which i think the army's response becomes more and more strong armed response which we saw

00:48:14.720 --> 00:48:20.400
[Guest]: in south kashmir which we saw in the in the photograph of that of the gentleman being taken

00:48:20.400 --> 00:48:26.320
[Guest]: on a burnout of a jeep and all those kind of visual public images which were not condemned by

00:48:26.320 --> 00:48:30.720
[Guest]: the state or people were not punished for those transgressions but being justified and in some

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:35.440
[Guest]: cases even being rewarded for what they were doing at that point in time and i think that's the

00:48:35.440 --> 00:48:40.000
[Guest]: journey kashmir has seen in some ways it's not been a happy journey for kashmiris it's not been

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:44.800
[Guest]: a happy journey for the army i don't think any institution benefits by being in this kind of

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:50.480
[Guest]: environment for a long period of time and probably there was a time when things could have been

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:55.280
[Guest]: settled better if the state administration had been much more stronger much more powerful if

00:48:55.280 --> 00:49:00.080
[Guest]: the army had been more willing to take certain amount of risk if pakistan was not as perfidious

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:04.400
[Guest]: as it was if probably afghanistan was not in turmoil and the americans were not trying to

00:49:04.400 --> 00:49:10.080
[Guest]: pacify it with pakistani support all those kind of things what ifs there are a lot of counterfactual

00:49:10.080 --> 00:49:14.560
[Guest]: there are a lot of what ifs that can be used but unfortunately now we are at a point in kashmir

00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:19.200
[Guest]: where it looks pretty bad from the perspective of the kashmiris any kashmiri you speak to

00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:24.400
[Guest]: doesn't really have nice things to say about the the indian state and that's pretty hurtful for

00:49:24.400 --> 00:49:29.440
[Amit Varma]: most of us yeah no that chronology dovetails exactly what with what devdas describes in his

00:49:29.440 --> 00:49:35.120
[Amit Varma]: book in fact earlier i said the watch by nawaz sharif talks but spoken typo obviously i meant

00:49:35.120 --> 00:49:39.600
[Amit Varma]: watched by musharraf so around 2003 it starts getting better but what happens and this is

00:49:39.600 --> 00:49:44.640
[Amit Varma]: probably not just an army issue it's a bsf issue it's a police issue like devdas in his book writes

00:49:44.640 --> 00:49:49.040
[Amit Varma]: about how the people who became senior police officers in the late aughties were people who

00:49:49.040 --> 00:49:53.520
[Amit Varma]: grew up at the height of the insurrection so they were used to strong arm methods there was

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:58.240
[Amit Varma]: massive rent seeking because the state was using its power there was daily humiliation like at one

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:03.600
[Amit Varma]: point he writes quote most men had at some point been abused slapped or kicked on their way after

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:07.920
[Amit Varma]: a soldier had looked at their id card or they had watched a father or an uncle being slapped

00:50:07.920 --> 00:50:12.240
[Amit Varma]: or ordered to do squats while holding his ears or made to stand on his hands with his feet propped

00:50:12.240 --> 00:50:16.800
[Amit Varma]: against a wall on a public road while neighbors and relatives passed by humiliation was one of

00:50:16.800 --> 00:50:21.920
[Amit Varma]: the keys to control stop quote entirely sounding worse than the british were with us and the

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:27.360
[Amit Varma]: question here is how do we think of something like legitimacy like you actually served in

00:50:27.360 --> 00:50:32.480
[Amit Varma]: kashmir at one point in the early 90s and like you said this is in the first phase where a lot

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:37.840
[Amit Varma]: of the militancy was coming from outside you've said that the locals trusted the army more than

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:42.800
[Amit Varma]: the militants and in a sense they are caught between a rock and a hard place but this question

00:50:42.800 --> 00:50:46.880
[Amit Varma]: of how legitimate you are considered to me is really important because if you're not considered

00:50:46.880 --> 00:50:53.280
[Amit Varma]: legitimate if you're looked upon as an occupier then every arrest is an abduction everyone who

00:50:53.280 --> 00:50:58.800
[Amit Varma]: every local who dies for whatever reason it can be looked upon as a murder so what was your

00:50:58.800 --> 00:51:05.280
[Amit Varma]: experience there in kashmir like did it evolve over a period of time and do you feel that in a

00:51:05.280 --> 00:51:09.520
[Amit Varma]: sense you know like going back to that whole counterinsurgency formula that is 20 percent

00:51:09.520 --> 00:51:14.240
[Amit Varma]: military and 80 percent political is that something you agree with and was this something that the

00:51:14.240 --> 00:51:19.040
[Amit Varma]: army was not equipped to do that you are equipped to win the military part of it how the hell do you

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:24.240
[Amit Varma]: do the rest of it in hindsight when we look back at that period what are the kind of failings that

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:29.680
[Amit Varma]: one can see and would have would the army having learned from all of those lessons be in a better

00:51:29.680 --> 00:51:34.560
[Amit Varma]: place to do the job if you had to sort of in a groundhog kind of groundhog day kind of way

00:51:34.560 --> 00:51:41.440
[Guest]: relive history again two things one is that the army actually acted against a lot of misdemeanors

00:51:41.440 --> 00:51:46.480
[Guest]: so i will not say that every misdemeanor was punished but everything wrong that was reported

00:51:46.480 --> 00:51:50.800
[Guest]: or brought into the public domain people did get punished you know people went behind bars people

00:51:50.800 --> 00:51:55.440
[Guest]: suffered for their you know putting their promotions all those things they were not taken lightly in

00:51:55.440 --> 00:51:59.600
[Guest]: that sense maybe the reason may not be human rights per se the reason maybe that you did the

00:51:59.600 --> 00:52:03.440
[Guest]: institution did not want the discipline to go down maybe the reason was that institution did

00:52:03.440 --> 00:52:08.240
[Guest]: not want it to be perceived badly by the public a larger public large indian public maybe that's

00:52:08.240 --> 00:52:12.880
[Guest]: the the narrative in the country was different the larger political administrative setup in the

00:52:12.880 --> 00:52:16.160
[Guest]: government in the country thought different maybe the courts in the country thought differently at

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:20.800
[Guest]: that point in time so there was no reward for doing something wrong you know if you got caught

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:25.040
[Guest]: you know you were in trouble there's no doubt about that and people did get punished for it

00:52:25.040 --> 00:52:28.800
[Guest]: that that's something which we must recognize so it's not that as if it was free for all that

00:52:28.800 --> 00:52:33.120
[Guest]: everything that went unpunished and went or was rewarded in that place that's not true in army's

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:37.520
[Guest]: defense i must say that in the defense of the security forces or the or the indian state now

00:52:37.520 --> 00:52:40.960
[Guest]: that's debatable whether it was up to the right extent when it should have been done whether it

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:45.200
[Guest]: really really allowed us to build the trust and you know we have the examples of the americans in

00:52:45.200 --> 00:52:50.240
[Guest]: vietnam americans in afghanistan iraq you know this is a whole debate which is like none of us

00:52:50.240 --> 00:52:55.200
[Guest]: have the answers to that debate in that sense could the army have provided the final solution

00:52:55.200 --> 00:53:00.320
[Guest]: or the and i'm not using the final solution in the term not not in court unfortunate choice of words

00:53:01.600 --> 00:53:06.400
[Guest]: sorry you know could the army have provided a more lasting permanent solution to the problem

00:53:06.400 --> 00:53:11.280
[Guest]: in that sense on its own i don't think that was possible by the very nature of the army

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:18.080
[Guest]: without the other arms of the state taking their responsibility including the political leadership

00:53:18.080 --> 00:53:24.640
[Guest]: and being supported by the central in a big way and those opportunities were there at multiple

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:30.000
[Guest]: points in time especially when the violence has subsided in the early 2010s and then in the earlier

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:35.280
[Guest]: part of the previous decade there was a possibility that something like you know you remember the

00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:40.960
[Guest]: debate around the removal of afspa from urban areas of kashmir which was supported by mr pijat

00:53:40.960 --> 00:53:45.360
[Guest]: ambram as the home minister and others but the upward was opposed by the army and the defense

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:49.920
[Guest]: ministry and the then defense minister ak antony and it could not be removed there were moments

00:53:49.920 --> 00:53:53.920
[Guest]: which were not grasped in kashmir very clearly and you know these were movements which were not

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:58.960
[Guest]: grasped politically more than by the military i would not want the military to go and start

00:53:58.960 --> 00:54:03.840
[Guest]: telling the politician how to do politics you know that would be more like pakistan than with india

00:54:03.840 --> 00:54:08.640
[Guest]: so yeah military was doing what it was being told to do what it thought was the right thing to do

00:54:08.640 --> 00:54:13.200
[Guest]: within the domain of independence that it was given within the task that it was given

00:54:13.200 --> 00:54:16.960
[Guest]: there were mistakes made i think everybody in the army would accept that there were mistakes made

00:54:16.960 --> 00:54:21.280
[Guest]: some of them went unpunished some of them were of course punished things could have been done

00:54:21.280 --> 00:54:27.200
[Guest]: better things would have been done in a much smarter way much better way and but the nature

00:54:27.200 --> 00:54:32.640
[Guest]: of the organization the nature of the institution the certain inherent characteristics through which

00:54:32.640 --> 00:54:37.440
[Guest]: the military looks at various roles and military is not the police for a reason or not the

00:54:37.440 --> 00:54:41.920
[Guest]: gendarmerie or the paramilitary for a reason to come into play because you at the end of the day

00:54:41.920 --> 00:54:46.400
[Guest]: you do not want to reduce the military to a paramilitary force or to a police force because

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:50.720
[Guest]: it has to deal with an external enemy and deal with an external entity there's a psychological

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:56.240
[Guest]: mindset of the organization of the institution which is different from other security forces

00:54:56.240 --> 00:55:01.760
[Guest]: and which does come into play at many points in time it is also that you know if the paramilitary

00:55:01.760 --> 00:55:05.200
[Guest]: forces fail they will call in the army if the police fails they'll call in the paramilitary

00:55:05.200 --> 00:55:09.760
[Guest]: forces but if the army fails whom do you call in you know you really cannot call in anybody so

00:55:10.320 --> 00:55:16.080
[Guest]: i think that pressure of having to succeed you know if i fail then there's nothing after me

00:55:16.080 --> 00:55:20.160
[Guest]: it's almost like the number seven or number eight batsman in cricket if i failed the pressure of

00:55:20.160 --> 00:55:24.640
[Guest]: somebody you know batting at that other thing i'm trivializing the matter but but what i'm saying is

00:55:24.640 --> 00:55:31.040
[Guest]: that nothing after me you know i'm so i really need to so you know people can make decisions

00:55:31.040 --> 00:55:35.200
[Guest]: under that kind of pressure which are not the decisions they would look back very fondly at

00:55:35.200 --> 00:55:41.280
[Guest]: a few years down the line and i think that's how i would characterize it that's how i would

00:55:41.280 --> 00:55:46.560
[Amit Varma]: i would put it across yeah that analogy about the number seven batsman is spoken like a true

00:55:46.560 --> 00:55:52.400
[Amit Varma]: 80s kid because this was true in the 80s number seven out but today today we have such pleasant

00:55:52.400 --> 00:55:58.320
[Amit Varma]: batting depth so you know again to come out of the army context just as someone who's kind of

00:55:58.320 --> 00:56:03.360
[Amit Varma]: lived in kashmir and i assume you have some familiarity and affection which goes beyond

00:56:03.920 --> 00:56:08.480
[Amit Varma]: whatever your army experience might have been what do you feel when you look at it today like

00:56:08.480 --> 00:56:12.000
[Amit Varma]: i thought what happened a couple of years back and of course i had a great episode on this with

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:16.400
[Amit Varma]: our mutual friend srinath raghavan i remember being very despondent at the time because i

00:56:16.400 --> 00:56:20.880
[Amit Varma]: thought india has lost kashmir for two decades like i cannot and especially after what has

00:56:20.880 --> 00:56:25.600
[Amit Varma]: happened since where for months and months they have no internet and i mean everything that

00:56:25.600 --> 00:56:31.120
[Amit Varma]: happened just felt that it was a huge turning point towards the worst what's your sense of

00:56:32.080 --> 00:56:36.400
[Guest]: all of that yeah that episode with srinath was by the way a great episode srinath is a very dear

00:56:36.400 --> 00:56:41.840
[Guest]: friend srinath is a very dear friend and what more can i say actually i mean it's very very sad in

00:56:41.840 --> 00:56:46.000
[Guest]: fact you know that kashmir is the place that it is in and the kashmiris had to undergo all that

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:51.360
[Guest]: they have undergone in the last couple of last couple of years including denial of basic rights

00:56:51.360 --> 00:56:57.600
[Guest]: like the whether it be internet or whether it be freedom to move or to do other things and the

00:56:57.600 --> 00:57:04.080
[Guest]: whole characterization of kashmiris as being something different from indians and i'm saying

00:57:04.080 --> 00:57:08.560
[Guest]: indians in the inverted commas the way the whole narrative has been framed on certain news

00:57:08.560 --> 00:57:14.240
[Guest]: television channels and the way it has been politically exploited leaves me very very

00:57:14.240 --> 00:57:18.800
[Guest]: despondent and you know it's it raises the fundamental question are we in kashmir for

00:57:18.800 --> 00:57:25.520
[Guest]: the land or are we in kashmir also for the people you know we really have let the kashmiris down

00:57:25.520 --> 00:57:32.400
[Guest]: in a big way and for all those of us who think that we may not speak for kashmiris today because

00:57:32.400 --> 00:57:36.240
[Guest]: it doesn't really matter they are one part of the thing and they have a different history

00:57:36.240 --> 00:57:42.240
[Guest]: narrative context may realize sooner or rather than later that it can then come to other parts

00:57:42.240 --> 00:57:47.040
[Guest]: of the of the country as well one of my closest friends who's a very reputed kashmiri journalist

00:57:47.040 --> 00:57:51.520
[Guest]: and i'm not going to name him here but he says that guys don't think that what's happening in

00:57:51.520 --> 00:57:55.840
[Guest]: kashmir won't happen in india tomorrow a lot of this is what is being tried there is then being

00:57:55.840 --> 00:58:02.240
[Guest]: used in the rest of the country so i think that's something indians if not for out of any altruistic

00:58:02.240 --> 00:58:08.400
[Guest]: motives or you know reasons of ideology at least for their self-preservation and for their

00:58:08.400 --> 00:58:15.200
[Guest]: self-interest a lot of people should actually think about kashmiris and stand in their support or

00:58:15.200 --> 00:58:20.320
[Guest]: not allow the violation of human rights in kashmir to the extent that has happened in the last couple

00:58:20.320 --> 00:58:26.400
[Amit Varma]: of years at least no it's tragic and i actually lament while uh that it might even be too late

00:58:26.400 --> 00:58:31.120
[Amit Varma]: for that slide i mean it reminds you of the naimola poem right where first they came for a and i didn't

00:58:31.120 --> 00:58:34.960
[Amit Varma]: speak up and then they came for b and then they came for c and then they came for d and then they

00:58:34.960 --> 00:58:39.040
[Amit Varma]: came for me and there was no one to speak up for me broadly and you see right in fact playing out

00:58:39.040 --> 00:58:45.200
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that when 370 was repealed kejriwal actually became a cheerleader for the government

00:58:45.200 --> 00:58:50.000
[Amit Varma]: and put out that tweet about how he supports a move and now they've come for him and now they've

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:54.640
[Amit Varma]: come for delhi and what are you going to do and the larger mindset which applies to all of us and

00:58:54.640 --> 00:59:00.480
[Amit Varma]: and your friend is absolutely right when he says that it holds a lesson for all of us the larger

00:59:00.480 --> 00:59:05.120
[Amit Varma]: mindset is that the state looks at itself as a colonial state did in the sense that they are

00:59:05.120 --> 00:59:11.040
[Amit Varma]: our rulers and we are the subjects and the moment you become subjects and not citizens

00:59:11.040 --> 00:59:15.840
[Amit Varma]: then everything is up for grabs and first it happened to the kashmiris but there's no reason

00:59:15.840 --> 00:59:21.120
[Amit Varma]: that if that mindset is pervasive and it mindset is even pervasive in the people not just in the

00:59:21.120 --> 00:59:28.320
[Amit Varma]: state then what are you kind of going to do about it so yeah so amit the whole point is as you

00:59:28.320 --> 00:59:33.600
[Guest]: rightly said uh citizens not subjects and these citizens what is the difference between a citizen

00:59:33.600 --> 00:59:40.880
[Guest]: and a subject that a citizen has certain inalienable no rights which are bestowed upon

00:59:40.880 --> 00:59:47.200
[Guest]: and it is essentially we do not see those rights being spoken of we see that trust the state trust

00:59:47.200 --> 00:59:52.720
[Guest]: an individual you know he's giving you this she's giving you that take it and be happy you know so

00:59:52.720 --> 00:59:57.360
[Guest]: and so so much of amount of money is coming it's not that i have certain rights which are which

00:59:57.360 --> 01:00:02.000
[Guest]: are enshrined to me and which are enshrined to me not only in the indian constitution

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:09.440
[Guest]: but even without the indian constitution as a human being amit many people forget that the

01:00:09.440 --> 01:00:15.600
[Guest]: cases for habeas corpus which were upheld by the various high courts during the emergency

01:00:15.600 --> 01:00:19.440
[Guest]: and this is beautifully explained in pratina vanil and christophe jeffrello's new book on

01:00:19.440 --> 01:00:24.720
[Guest]: the emergency were not upheld because of the constitution because constitution was an abeyance

01:00:24.720 --> 01:00:29.680
[Guest]: fundamental rights were never they were upheld on the grounds that certain rights are inalienable

01:00:29.680 --> 01:00:35.840
[Guest]: to a person to a human being with or without the constitution and habeas corpus is one of those

01:00:35.840 --> 01:00:41.280
[Guest]: rights in today's times the habeas corpus is not being upheld you know you habeas corpus petitions

01:00:41.280 --> 01:00:47.920
[Guest]: have been lying for for months a habeas corpus is the very basic fundamental right of democracy

01:00:47.920 --> 01:00:52.160
[Guest]: how can you have a liberal democracy if habeas corpus is not being upheld the supreme court

01:00:52.160 --> 01:00:56.240
[Guest]: with due respect you know and i you and i may be charged for contempt of court but supreme

01:00:56.240 --> 01:01:00.560
[Guest]: court with due respect saying that you know you can go but not do politics okay go and see him

01:01:00.560 --> 01:01:05.280
[Guest]: don't touch him you know to give him medicine but don't do this that is not habeas corpus present

01:01:05.280 --> 01:01:10.800
[Guest]: the guy why is he being kept behind bar or the fact that mehbooba mufti or or farooq abdullah

01:01:10.800 --> 01:01:14.880
[Guest]: or omar abdullah the gates were being shut down during the ddc elections and they're not being

01:01:14.880 --> 01:01:20.080
