[Amit Varma]: there is that nuclear deterrent in place the actual conventional army while it needs to exist

01:34:24.720 --> 01:34:29.440
[Amit Varma]: in practical terms could be a bit of an artifact because you're never having a conventional war

01:34:29.440 --> 01:34:35.040
[Amit Varma]: there is a threshold you will never cross because the danger of going nuclear is simply too high

01:34:35.040 --> 01:34:40.400
[Amit Varma]: in a sense both india and pakistan going nuclear has actually taken away our advantage like whatever

01:34:40.400 --> 01:34:44.960
[Amit Varma]: advantage we had in conventional terms is now equalized because in a game theory sense you

01:34:44.960 --> 01:34:49.920
[Amit Varma]: are never going to go beyond a certain threshold you will have you know the optics of balakot and

01:34:49.920 --> 01:34:54.640
[Amit Varma]: surgical strikes and all of that to satisfy the local political constituency and we we'll discuss

01:34:54.640 --> 01:35:00.800
[Amit Varma]: that later as well but then the question is that how is the army to think of itself like on the

01:35:00.800 --> 01:35:05.760
[Amit Varma]: one hand you pointed out about how the chinese army is modernizing with ai and robotics and all

01:35:05.760 --> 01:35:10.800
[Amit Varma]: that i am guessing that there must be many aspects of the indian armed forces which are actually

01:35:10.800 --> 01:35:15.200
[Amit Varma]: redundant in terms of technology how are we to think of that and how is the army to think of

01:35:15.200 --> 01:35:22.320
[Amit Varma]: itself when the army needs to exist to be sort of a pawn in the geopolitical games but is never

01:35:22.320 --> 01:35:27.600
[Amit Varma]: actually going to be used that seems to be a certain kind of school of thought that is out

01:35:27.600 --> 01:35:33.840
[Guest]: there so what's your response yeah so there are two ways i look at it so i'll expand it to more

01:35:33.840 --> 01:35:38.640
[Guest]: than the army the armed forces so the armed forces will have a role to play the navy perhaps in the

01:35:38.640 --> 01:35:42.880
[Guest]: in the indian ocean region because it's such a important region trade wise if you dominate the

01:35:42.880 --> 01:35:46.080
[Guest]: indian ocean region you control a lot of this thing and you can put pressure on various countries

01:35:46.080 --> 01:35:50.800
[Guest]: including china you can wave the indian flag a clearly a blue water navy would be a great idea

01:35:50.800 --> 01:35:55.120
[Guest]: and that's what navy has been advocating for itself for the last two decades if not more at

01:35:55.120 --> 01:35:59.120
[Guest]: least 2025 years that they've been advocating that we want to be a really a blue water navy

01:35:59.120 --> 01:36:04.000
[Guest]: a three carrier navy to be able to take our take the indian flag far and far and wide and really

01:36:04.000 --> 01:36:08.800
[Guest]: be controlling the indian ocean in the sense what the the inverse of what china says china says

01:36:08.800 --> 01:36:14.240
[Guest]: indian ocean is not india's ocean when india says you know i want to make indian ocean india's ocean

01:36:14.240 --> 01:36:21.360
[Guest]: in that sense for the army particularly the whole idea is that how do we find a way in which we can

01:36:21.360 --> 01:36:28.240
[Guest]: impose the nation's will on an adversary under the nuclear threshold so the whole idea the whole

01:36:28.240 --> 01:36:36.720
[Guest]: strategy the whole thing is can i do something by moving in quickly what was called the cold start

01:36:36.720 --> 01:36:41.600
[Guest]: later on called the proactive operations poa whatever the name you may want to give to it

01:36:41.600 --> 01:36:47.200
[Guest]: the whole idea is can i move in quickly grab a certain piece of territory or a certain piece

01:36:47.200 --> 01:36:54.720
[Guest]: of valuable territory with or break the adversary center of gravity so to speak so and do it rather

01:36:54.720 --> 01:36:59.440
[Guest]: quickly and under the nuclear threshold so that it comes to the negotiating table or concedes or

01:36:59.440 --> 01:37:04.640
[Guest]: listens or whatever you wanted to get it done or even humiliate it or even threaten it that's the

01:37:04.640 --> 01:37:11.280
[Guest]: way the armed forces have responded to the changing our dynamics of having the nuclear weapons amit

01:37:11.280 --> 01:37:16.000
[Guest]: let's also understand that nuclear weapons at the end of the day are political weapons the indian

01:37:16.000 --> 01:37:22.240
[Guest]: armed forces do not control the nuclear nuclear weapons are controlled politically and whatever

01:37:22.240 --> 01:37:27.920
[Guest]: would happen would happen as a decision as a political decision not as a military decision

01:37:27.920 --> 01:37:32.080
[Guest]: in pakistan gulam isaac khan handed over the nuclear weapons to the military even in pakistan

01:37:32.080 --> 01:37:36.000
[Guest]: they were not controlled by the military and now they are they become military weapons especially

01:37:36.000 --> 01:37:40.240
[Guest]: they are brought in these short-range tactical nuclear weapons and they brought in these small

01:37:40.240 --> 01:37:44.960
[Guest]: missiles they are almost you know using them at the lowest in the army for to threaten india that

01:37:44.960 --> 01:37:49.440
[Guest]: that go nuclear which is not the case in india so when the military operates or when the military

01:37:49.440 --> 01:37:57.200
[Guest]: plans for its operations it really does not factor in nuclear weapons at the in the first instance

01:37:57.760 --> 01:38:04.000
[Guest]: and there's a very high bar for use of nuclear weapons since hiroshima and nagasaki you know

01:38:04.000 --> 01:38:09.520
[Guest]: we saw that during the korean war and since then there's a very very high bar for use of nuclear

01:38:09.520 --> 01:38:16.560
[Guest]: weapons it would really take something for even pakistan or india to even threaten the use of

01:38:16.560 --> 01:38:22.480
[Guest]: nuclear weapons or to use them so even you gave the example of balakur the fact that indians

01:38:22.480 --> 01:38:28.400
[Guest]: went and attempted an airstrike did an airstrike inside pakistan proper uh the fact that pakistan

01:38:28.400 --> 01:38:32.880
[Guest]: that then the indians threatened a missile strike pakistanis threatened a missile strike

01:38:32.880 --> 01:38:39.120
[Guest]: and prime minister modi went and said in election speech that we haven't kept them for for diwali

01:38:39.120 --> 01:38:47.600
[Guest]: but the fact is that nuclear weapons still remain a distant thing in the india pakistan calculus

01:38:47.600 --> 01:38:51.600
[Guest]: what that red line is we really don't know well i don't know what pakistan's red line is we can all

01:38:51.600 --> 01:38:55.600
[Guest]: keep on assessing that red line and i always believe it's a it's a dynamic red line what

01:38:55.600 --> 01:39:01.200
[Guest]: india's red line whether we china is if there's a red line what is it and that probably keeps on

01:39:01.200 --> 01:39:06.560
[Guest]: varying depending on time and place i think uh while the nuclear weapons have affected the way

01:39:06.560 --> 01:39:11.520
[Guest]: wars are fought kargil happened after the nuclear weapons had come into play india mobilized in

01:39:11.520 --> 01:39:16.960
[Guest]: parakram after nuclear weapons and based on after parakram india decided to undertake a new thinking

01:39:16.960 --> 01:39:23.200
[Guest]: on cold start operations proactive operations etc and i think that's how the thinking is going on

01:39:23.200 --> 01:39:28.160
[Guest]: currently within the armed forces with the way they are they are trying to operate in this

01:39:28.160 --> 01:39:32.880
[Amit Varma]: environment so tell me about parakram because you actually served there you were actually

01:39:32.880 --> 01:39:38.160
[Amit Varma]: as you mentioned you know at the border and all of that waiting to take the indian flag to lahore

01:39:38.160 --> 01:39:44.080
[Amit Varma]: and just kind of planted there you know how much of it was theater how much of it was actually

01:39:44.080 --> 01:39:49.440
[Amit Varma]: preparing for war should it happen like at that moment in time what did you think the probabilities

01:39:49.440 --> 01:39:53.920
[Amit Varma]: were what did you find more desirable and even there of course probabilistic thinking comes

01:39:53.920 --> 01:39:58.720
[Amit Varma]: into play how far would we need to be pushed before we actually went to war for example which

01:39:58.720 --> 01:40:04.160
[Amit Varma]: is a separate question and i can ask you right with your current hat on so tell me a little bit

01:40:04.160 --> 01:40:09.520
[Amit Varma]: about that and then also how the dynamic of india pakistan relationships have been playing out since

01:40:09.520 --> 01:40:14.000
[Amit Varma]: because like you pointed out you know 9 11 kind of changed a lot there i remember traveling through

01:40:14.000 --> 01:40:19.360
[Amit Varma]: pakistan to cover a cricket tour in 2006 but i was also writing pieces for the wall street journal

01:40:19.360 --> 01:40:26.240
[Amit Varma]: and one economist i met there said that listen we don't call al-qaeda al-qaeda we call it al-faida

01:40:26.240 --> 01:40:30.560
[Amit Varma]: because of all the money that flooded into pakistan after that happened and obviously

01:40:30.560 --> 01:40:34.720
[Amit Varma]: then they would because pakistan was helping them with the so-called war on terror they would

01:40:34.720 --> 01:40:40.240
[Amit Varma]: you know the us would turn a blind eye to what was happening in india and and all of that so

01:40:40.240 --> 01:40:45.280
[Amit Varma]: there's that interesting dynamic playing out how has that relationship kind of evolved over the

01:40:45.280 --> 01:40:50.960
[Amit Varma]: last 20 years or so under of course a nuclear shadow but even apart from that just the politics

01:40:50.960 --> 01:40:56.240
[Guest]: of both countries so in prakram i was a very young officer so really not really understanding

01:40:56.240 --> 01:41:01.200
[Guest]: the larger dynamics of how probably the decisions were being taken but i can say that as a separate

01:41:01.200 --> 01:41:06.800
[Guest]: officer mines were laid by india on which is like the first preparatory stage before you go to war

01:41:06.800 --> 01:41:11.760
[Guest]: and actual live mines were laid a lot of casualties took place in bilingual mind there were accidents

01:41:11.760 --> 01:41:16.640
[Guest]: which are par for the course etc those things happened but there was serious preparation at

01:41:16.640 --> 01:41:22.400
[Guest]: that point in time and at one point in time it almost seemed that india had decided to go into

01:41:22.400 --> 01:41:27.680
[Guest]: pakistan and and launch a war clearly there was a lot of international pressure which came from

01:41:27.680 --> 01:41:33.680
[Guest]: the us primarily and from others and which stopped eventually stopped india and then there was a

01:41:33.680 --> 01:41:37.520
[Guest]: whole theory then there's a lot of lot of lot has been written about it whether india genuinely

01:41:37.520 --> 01:41:41.520
[Guest]: wanted to go to war and only wanted to convey to the west that we are serious and therefore

01:41:41.520 --> 01:41:45.760
[Guest]: took all those steps because how do you credibly convey that they are serious and which brought

01:41:45.760 --> 01:41:49.520
[Guest]: Musharraf to make those announcements on the Lashkar-e-Toiba and the Jaish-e-Mohammad which

01:41:49.520 --> 01:41:54.640
[Guest]: he made on live television and then the Indian army pulled back from the borders there were a

01:41:54.640 --> 01:41:59.520
[Guest]: couple of things which happened very clearly that the mobilization timings the timing for the forces

01:41:59.520 --> 01:42:04.720
[Guest]: to mobilize from their permanent locations to the to the forward lines those timings were just not

01:42:04.720 --> 01:42:08.480
[Guest]: kept up by the army and there's something which came out in all these study reports after the war

01:42:08.480 --> 01:42:12.640
[Guest]: they took a lot of time to really reach those forward lines you know so if something was

01:42:12.640 --> 01:42:19.120
[Guest]: planned to reach in 10 days they took 30 days 35 days 40 days to reach so that completely upset all

01:42:19.120 --> 01:42:23.600
[Guest]: the planning that had gone on till then and clearly showed that some of the planning was unrealistic

01:42:23.600 --> 01:42:28.160
[Guest]: that is what led to the whole idea of cold start operations can you move certain forward and because

01:42:28.160 --> 01:42:32.400
[Guest]: the window is very short before the western countries western powers intervene can you

01:42:32.400 --> 01:42:37.360
[Guest]: use that window to quickly go in rather than having this massive second world war kind of

01:42:37.360 --> 01:42:41.680
[Guest]: mobilization where it takes months for you to reach the border and then decide to go to war

01:42:41.680 --> 01:42:45.840
[Guest]: and by the time western leaderships and western diplomats have come in and put pressure on you so

01:42:45.840 --> 01:42:52.000
[Guest]: as not to go that was the one big change which took place after Parakram but that has not been

01:42:52.000 --> 01:42:57.520
[Guest]: tested so far and has not been checked by or tested on the ground by the by India since but

01:42:57.520 --> 01:43:02.640
[Guest]: a lot of talk a lot of discussion a lot of practice a lot of rehearsals have taken place on that what

01:43:02.640 --> 01:43:09.520
[Guest]: is the dynamics between India and Pakistan when it comes to proactive operations cold start Pakistan

01:43:09.520 --> 01:43:14.640
[Guest]: has milked the whole idea that India will launch cold start operations will do proactive operations

01:43:14.640 --> 01:43:19.920
[Guest]: to the maximum it has of course prepared for it under Kayani they conducted multiple exercises

01:43:19.920 --> 01:43:24.320
[Guest]: where they practiced and rehearsed their responses to it and they claim that they are better prepared

01:43:24.320 --> 01:43:29.120
[Guest]: for it and they also claim that they brought the tactical nuclear weapons the Hath missiles to

01:43:29.120 --> 01:43:32.880
[Guest]: deal with this kind of challenge because the Indian army would move in very very quickly and

01:43:32.880 --> 01:43:38.000
[Guest]: occupy certain territory and the only way for them to stop it was to fire certain tactical nuclear

01:43:38.000 --> 01:43:42.960
[Guest]: weapons which are like low output nuclear weapons so that is the kind of dynamics that has taken

01:43:42.960 --> 01:43:48.960
[Guest]: place because of Parakram and what happened after the attack on Indian parliament but that's that's

01:43:48.960 --> 01:43:54.320
[Amit Varma]: kind of fascinating and and you know the other part of the question that I asked was that assume

01:43:54.320 --> 01:44:00.480
[Amit Varma]: that you are in charge of sort of a decision making what is the threshold at which you say

01:44:00.480 --> 01:44:05.680
[Amit Varma]: that okay we have to move in now we have to actually go to war or is there no threshold

01:44:05.680 --> 01:44:10.800
[Amit Varma]: because the nuclear option is just too expensive and if there is no threshold if you are never

01:44:10.800 --> 01:44:15.200
[Amit Varma]: actually going to war if you're just going to posture then the other side surely knows that

01:44:15.200 --> 01:44:20.560
[Amit Varma]: and can take advantage of that right so you know how does that sort of it's almost a game

01:44:20.560 --> 01:44:25.360
[Amit Varma]: theoretic situation except that it's not actually chicken chicken because both sides know the other

01:44:25.360 --> 01:44:31.760
[Amit Varma]: one won't be crazy enough but who's going to stop first yeah so it is clearly a game theory

01:44:31.760 --> 01:44:36.560
[Guest]: does apply there and that's what will decide how the call is taken what is it that you want the

01:44:36.560 --> 01:44:41.360
[Guest]: adversary to do and if it concedes then you don't do it then your threat is clearly credible how

01:44:41.360 --> 01:44:45.680
[Guest]: credible is your threat is the question and to have a credible threat you need to have the armed

01:44:45.680 --> 01:44:51.440
[Guest]: forces what will be the reasons for which India would go to war my sense is a very big terror

01:44:51.440 --> 01:44:57.040
[Guest]: attack on Indian soil which can be seen to have come from Pakistan and where Pakistan is unwilling

01:44:57.040 --> 01:45:03.200
[Guest]: to punish those terrorist leaders or hand them over to India and then that would lead to a kind

01:45:03.200 --> 01:45:08.480
[Guest]: of retaliation on Pakistan and the other situation is that there is too much of political instability

01:45:08.480 --> 01:45:13.520
[Guest]: in Pakistan and a mad Pakistani leader tries to capture Kashmir regain Kashmir for whatever reason

01:45:13.520 --> 01:45:17.920
[Guest]: something you know a leader military leader which is far ahead of Musharraf in that sense

01:45:17.920 --> 01:45:22.960
[Guest]: and tries to recapture Kashmir and tries to try some funny things that would of course India would

01:45:22.960 --> 01:45:27.920
[Guest]: clearly open up a conventional military option conventional military war at that point I think

01:45:27.920 --> 01:45:34.240
[Guest]: those are the two scenarios where I think India would go in for a conventional war and whether

01:45:34.240 --> 01:45:40.160
[Guest]: this would lead to the nuclear option being exercised or nuclear option coming into play

01:45:40.160 --> 01:45:45.440
[Guest]: is something which every single analyst has debated and written about and spoken about

01:45:45.440 --> 01:45:50.160
[Guest]: and I don't think anybody has an answer but I think everybody will agree that there is an

01:45:50.160 --> 01:45:55.840
[Guest]: inherent risk involved in the escalation ladder so if you think that you are the one controlling

01:45:55.840 --> 01:45:59.520
[Guest]: the escalation ladder there are two sides playing the game and you know there are a

01:45:59.520 --> 01:46:04.400
[Guest]: lot of miscommunication and misapprehensions happening at the same time and it can clearly

01:46:04.400 --> 01:46:09.520
[Guest]: lead to situations where the escalation ladder may not be controlled by you and I think that's

01:46:09.520 --> 01:46:14.400
[Guest]: something which everybody worries about that is something which nobody knows how it will play out

01:46:14.400 --> 01:46:30.240
[Guest]: and I think that's something which which is what stops prevents makes people think twice before

01:46:30.240 --> 01:46:34.720
[Amit Varma]: committing to opening a front opening a conventional war going for a conventional war

01:46:34.720 --> 01:46:40.000
[Amit Varma]: no and it also strikes me that it is easy for us to get complacent and say that listen you know no

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:44.880
[Amit Varma]: nuclear weapons since hiroshima nagasaki so it's not going to happen and imagine that the situation

01:46:44.880 --> 01:46:49.680
[Amit Varma]: will last forever and i'm reminded of this beautiful book i'm reading right now by a german

01:46:49.680 --> 01:46:55.440
[Amit Varma]: writer called stefan schweig who led nazi germany and killed himself in 42 but just before that he

01:46:55.440 --> 01:46:59.520
[Amit Varma]: published this book called the world of yesterday where he's talking about the pre-world war one

01:46:59.520 --> 01:47:04.560
[Amit Varma]: years and he's essentially saying that we were under this liberal illusion that all our problems

01:47:04.560 --> 01:47:09.200
[Amit Varma]: are solved that you know a liberal vision of the world has won over there will be no more terrible

01:47:09.200 --> 01:47:14.640
[Amit Varma]: wars you know all these other problems like hunger famine etc will gradually solve and nothing will

01:47:14.640 --> 01:47:18.560
[Amit Varma]: happen and little did we know and and he's talking about this pre-world war thing where there is

01:47:18.560 --> 01:47:23.680
[Amit Varma]: almost like a fukuyama-esque end of history kind of sense to it that we've sorted everything it's

01:47:23.680 --> 01:47:28.480
[Amit Varma]: done and then suddenly everything goes nuts and when we talk of nuclear weapons i also think that

01:47:28.480 --> 01:47:33.120
[Amit Varma]: at some level it's kind of dangerous to think that nothing will ever happen this is all just

01:47:33.120 --> 01:47:37.440
[Amit Varma]: it's a political tool because you know of course nothing will happen until something does

01:47:37.440 --> 01:47:46.320
[Amit Varma]: and you know there's no reason to kind of assume complacency the other sort of difficult angle in

01:47:46.320 --> 01:47:52.400
[Amit Varma]: this is that this is not just two states it's not just the state of india and the state of pakistan

01:47:52.400 --> 01:47:56.640
[Amit Varma]: which determines what happens within india and pakistan like you've pointed out in this recent

01:47:56.640 --> 01:48:01.840
[Amit Varma]: piece you wrote on foreign policy quote talks can be derailed as much by a lone suicide bomber in

01:48:01.840 --> 01:48:08.320
[Amit Varma]: kashmir as by the powerful deep state in pakistan or by the stranded anti-pakistan hindu majoritarian

01:48:08.320 --> 01:48:13.520
[Amit Varma]: electoral agent of indian prime minister narendra modi stop quote the idea being that they can be

01:48:13.520 --> 01:48:19.120
[Amit Varma]: some lone rogue actor who can set something off and then there is of course a fog of war where

01:48:19.120 --> 01:48:23.600
[Amit Varma]: you don't know that what happened is this really the state of pakistan doing this are these rogue

01:48:23.600 --> 01:48:29.520
[Amit Varma]: actors within the deep state is it a lone suicide bomber possibly even a local guy in kashmir who's

01:48:29.520 --> 01:48:37.840
[Amit Varma]: doing all of this all of that uncertainty is also kind of built in so that complicates the

01:48:37.840 --> 01:48:42.560
[Guest]: whole situation so much more doesn't it yeah definitely i mean just going back to fukuyama

01:48:42.560 --> 01:48:47.920
[Guest]: you know the loveliest part of fukuyama's story is that his initial essay actually had a question

01:48:47.920 --> 01:48:52.400
[Amit Varma]: mark at the end of his title yeah it's a misunderstood essay he gets a lot of flack

01:48:52.400 --> 01:48:59.120
[Guest]: for it so you know the question mark completely changes everything as you know you know so that's

01:48:59.120 --> 01:49:03.360
[Guest]: so you know just that was an aside on the other statement that you made about the nuclear weapons

01:49:03.360 --> 01:49:07.760
[Guest]: you know give it there will never be a nuclear war no i don't think anybody should ever say that

01:49:07.760 --> 01:49:12.160
[Guest]: there will never be a nuclear war that would be complete the only question where i was what i was

01:49:12.160 --> 01:49:17.120
[Guest]: responding to was your premise that nuclear weapons have made the the indian armed forces

01:49:17.120 --> 01:49:21.920
[Guest]: redundant in a sense what i was saying is no there is they are not redundant they continue to exist

01:49:21.920 --> 01:49:26.000
[Amit Varma]: despite the nuclear weapons it was a you missed my question mark it was a question more than a

01:49:26.000 --> 01:49:31.440
[Guest]: premise yeah fair enough just to clarify because people may not be should not misunderstand it the

01:49:31.440 --> 01:49:35.280
[Guest]: whole idea is that despite the nuclear weapons the conventional military the conventional armed

01:49:35.280 --> 01:49:41.360
[Guest]: forces have a role to play which they have tried to reorient themselves for train themselves device

01:49:41.360 --> 01:49:46.080
[Guest]: for themselves it doesn't mean that the nuclear weapons cannot cannot be used or will not be used

01:49:46.080 --> 01:49:50.320
[Guest]: or there is some kind of that they are kept only as a showpiece which will never be used as far as

01:49:50.320 --> 01:49:55.920
[Guest]: the india pakistan relations are concerned there are many factors but i mean if india pakistan

01:49:55.920 --> 01:50:01.520
[Guest]: relations are to be considered the simple and the most fundamental factor is that there is a certain

01:50:01.520 --> 01:50:05.840
[Guest]: narrative on both the sides there's a narrative on the indian side and there's a narrative on

01:50:05.840 --> 01:50:13.600
[Guest]: the pakistani side that narrative is embedded in history in politics and religion in colonialism

01:50:13.600 --> 01:50:20.800
[Guest]: in every geopolitics in every single framework that the modern political socio-political world

01:50:20.800 --> 01:50:25.600
[Guest]: has it is embedded in every single thing in geography in history everything whatever we can

01:50:25.600 --> 01:50:31.440
[Guest]: think of that narrative is the fundamental structural factor where we believe that

01:50:31.440 --> 01:50:36.080
[Guest]: kashmir belongs to us and the pakistanis have occupied a certain part of kashmir including

01:50:36.080 --> 01:50:40.480
[Guest]: related pakistan which should come to us logically and we are going to take it at any cost whereas

01:50:40.480 --> 01:50:45.120
[Guest]: the pakistani side believes that kashmir has been grabbed by indians muslim majority state has to

01:50:45.120 --> 01:50:50.960
[Guest]: be part of that fundamental dissonance that fundamental gap has not been preached it is

01:50:50.960 --> 01:50:58.000
[Guest]: the structural factor unless we fix that narrative gap how are we going to fix the problem i don't

01:50:58.000 --> 01:51:03.200
[Guest]: see any kind of quick fixes where you can deal with it eventually as you see today when we are

01:51:03.200 --> 01:51:09.360
[Guest]: recording the show imran has sent a letter to modi responding to modi's letter of on 23rd march on

01:51:09.360 --> 01:51:13.440
[Guest]: pakistan day and imran has again said that the core issue is jammu and kashmir because prime

01:51:13.440 --> 01:51:18.000
[Guest]: minister modi had said that the core issue is uh terror that you know you please stop coming from

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:22.560
[Guest]: our side so fundamentally you know we are operating in a in within a structure where there are

01:51:22.560 --> 01:51:27.840
[Guest]: structurally it is not possible to align it these are two parallel tracks which will keep on going

01:51:27.840 --> 01:51:32.320
[Guest]: parallelly you know i'll keep on talking about terror they will keep on talking about kashmir

01:51:32.320 --> 01:51:38.800
[Guest]: unless the narrative is fixed you cannot align those two and everything else that uh you know

01:51:38.800 --> 01:51:43.760
[Guest]: that can lead to this whole process going kaput actually flows from that whether it is a terror

01:51:43.760 --> 01:51:48.720
[Guest]: alone terror attack like what happened in pulwama you know a 20 22 year old guy with a suicide

01:51:48.720 --> 01:51:55.200
[Guest]: with a car and a 20 kgs of explosive in his car banging into a CRPF bus or it is somebody else

01:51:55.200 --> 01:52:00.240
[Guest]: doing something similar or some elements of pakistan army uh who believe or deep state who

01:52:00.240 --> 01:52:05.120
[Guest]: believe that pakistan is conceding too much trying to you know try and do some stunts on from their

01:52:05.120 --> 01:52:09.760
[Guest]: side which has happened earlier as well from the pakistani side and of course there's a danger as

01:52:09.760 --> 01:52:14.960
[Guest]: you said mr modi's whole politics majoritarian uh hindu politics anti-pakistan narrative which

01:52:14.960 --> 01:52:19.200
[Guest]: he has used in various state assembly polls whether it is gujarat whether it is karnataka

01:52:19.200 --> 01:52:23.920
[Guest]: whether it is uttar pradesh pakistan has been a constant factor which has been in book how does

01:52:23.920 --> 01:52:29.200
[Guest]: he sell peace with pakistan when since 2002 you know you remember the mia musharraf campaign at

01:52:29.200 --> 01:52:34.480
[Guest]: that time he has always used pakistan as an enemy and trying to show himself as somebody who's trying

01:52:34.480 --> 01:52:40.160
[Guest]: to who has dealt with pakistan very efficiently and very effectively and very boldly so i do not

01:52:40.160 --> 01:52:45.840
[Guest]: know how this narrative how this problem of narrative in the on the indian side and on the

01:52:45.840 --> 01:52:52.960
[Guest]: pakistani side can be bridged which when merged with all these other problems of lone wolf lone

01:52:52.960 --> 01:52:58.400
[Guest]: terrorist with pakistani rogue state with indian dominant hindu majoritarian political ideology in

01:52:58.400 --> 01:53:03.280
[Guest]: india how do you fix this i i really don't know that there's so anybody who believes that this

01:53:03.280 --> 01:53:09.920
[Guest]: process is permanent irreversible and will lead to a solution of the problem needs to get a recheck

01:53:09.920 --> 01:53:17.040
[Guest]: i am not convinced that this solution is that easy and can be found so quickly the closest we

01:53:17.040 --> 01:53:21.680
[Guest]: came to solution is the time when you were in pakistan you know covering the cricket series

01:53:21.680 --> 01:53:25.280
[Guest]: that is the time we came with the four point formula etc and then the whole process got

01:53:25.280 --> 01:53:29.920
[Guest]: derailed on the pakistani side because musharraf got involved with that whole lawyer's crisis and

01:53:29.920 --> 01:53:34.080
[Guest]: then completely everything then stopped and then since then we have never been able to that's the

01:53:34.080 --> 01:53:38.560
[Guest]: closest we have come to this thing i have spoken to some senior indian diplomats who have dealt

01:53:38.560 --> 01:53:44.000
[Guest]: with pakistan over the years and they say that pakistan always overreaches either out of a

01:53:44.000 --> 01:53:47.760
[Guest]: certain defensiveness or out of certain aggressiveness whether it is bhutto talking

01:53:47.760 --> 01:53:53.520
[Guest]: to swaran singh uh after the 62 war uh you know trying to be very aggressive about uh about what

01:53:53.520 --> 01:53:59.440
[Guest]: pakistan wanted or you know bhutto in shimla after the 1971 war where he's trying to say oh

01:53:59.440 --> 01:54:04.080
[Guest]: please save me i'll be hanged if i concede you too much kind of a thing they have always overreached

01:54:04.080 --> 01:54:09.920
[Guest]: in a sense and that overreach has not allowed any solution to to come through of course the

01:54:09.920 --> 01:54:14.160
[Guest]: practical answer as most people would tell you sane people would tell you is that why don't

01:54:14.160 --> 01:54:18.000
[Guest]: you make the line of control the actual border and that is something which has been discussed

01:54:18.000 --> 01:54:21.840
[Guest]: since tashkent you know people who were at tashkent have said that this was discussed at

01:54:21.840 --> 01:54:25.680
[Guest]: tashkent as well and this was agreed almost informally between the two sides between ayub

01:54:25.680 --> 01:54:29.680
[Guest]: and shastri that we should make the line of control the international border at some point in

01:54:29.680 --> 01:54:34.000
[Guest]: time but i don't think now with the kind of narrative that we have and the kind of ideology

01:54:34.000 --> 01:54:38.080
[Guest]: that we have ruling on our side which believes in the whole idea of an akhand bharat which does

01:54:38.080 --> 01:54:42.800
[Guest]: not believe that partition was the right thing it would be very difficult for them for anyone to go

01:54:42.800 --> 01:54:48.160
[Guest]: and say okay that we are giving away pakistan occupied kashmir to pakistan or gilgit baltistan

01:54:48.160 --> 01:54:54.240
[Guest]: to pakistan and still take a very strident anti-pakistan line electorally in their election

01:54:54.240 --> 01:54:59.440
[Amit Varma]: campaigns here in india no and uh sort of three thoughts strike me while uh you know you were

01:55:00.000 --> 01:55:04.480
[Amit Varma]: talking just now and one of them is i agree that it seems and it's almost like israel palestine

01:55:04.480 --> 01:55:08.960
[Amit Varma]: issue that it doesn't seem to be a resolution because the narratives are just so opposed

01:55:08.960 --> 01:55:13.360
[Amit Varma]: having said that i think that the kashmir situation is one that could have resolved

01:55:13.360 --> 01:55:19.360
[Amit Varma]: itself through decades if we had only taken the effort to integrate kashmiris within our economy

01:55:19.360 --> 01:55:24.640
[Amit Varma]: in fact around that time that i was in pakistan around that time that you know musharraf and

01:55:24.640 --> 01:55:29.040
[Amit Varma]: vajpayee were talking about chilling out david devdas writes about how the youth of kashmir

01:55:29.040 --> 01:55:34.400
[Amit Varma]: at that time became aspirational they wanted to do mbas they wanted jobs they wanted all of that

01:55:34.400 --> 01:55:39.840
[Amit Varma]: but things just fell backwards from there and if things had gone in a different direction

01:55:39.840 --> 01:55:44.080
[Amit Varma]: and they could have felt that there is value in it for being part of this indian union maybe

01:55:44.080 --> 01:55:48.320
[Amit Varma]: things could have been different but that's an aside and amusing and anyway it is moot because

01:55:48.320 --> 01:55:53.680
[Amit Varma]: it is too late for that very sadly the other interesting part about narratives is one of

01:55:53.680 --> 01:56:00.160
[Amit Varma]: course there are the narratives about kashmir but then there is also this local sort of political

01:56:00.160 --> 01:56:04.800
[Amit Varma]: narrative this nationalistic narrative where pakistan is always the enemy where you keep

01:56:04.800 --> 01:56:09.440
[Amit Varma]: telling your enemies that you are anti-national go to pakistan you know it's become part of the

01:56:09.440 --> 01:56:16.800
[Amit Varma]: vocabulary in that sense so how do you see that danger of the narrative itself making reality go

01:56:16.800 --> 01:56:21.440
[Amit Varma]: in a certain direction like you know if the prime minister is in a political fix and you have no

01:56:21.440 --> 01:56:27.040
[Amit Varma]: option but to raise the kind of temperature like in fact what you know we saw with the surgical

01:56:27.040 --> 01:56:32.160
[Amit Varma]: strikes which you know luckily didn't lead to anything beyond that but where in fact you

01:56:32.160 --> 01:56:37.280
[Amit Varma]: inadvertently played a part in a little number that came out of that narrative so do take an

01:56:37.280 --> 01:56:42.320
[Amit Varma]: aside and tell us about that and then you can address a larger question yeah so the first the

01:56:42.320 --> 01:56:47.120
[Guest]: aside so essentially it happened that the army that the army was briefing that they announced

01:56:47.120 --> 01:56:53.840
[Guest]: these these these surgical strikes across the line of control and if i remember correctly now they

01:56:53.840 --> 01:56:59.520
[Guest]: said five places had been hit which were these points from which terrorists were being sent

01:56:59.520 --> 01:57:04.960
[Guest]: across and somebody a fellow journalist a television journalist for a hindi news channel

01:57:04.960 --> 01:57:08.800
[Guest]: actually asked me yes sir you have served in that area what does it mean how many people would be

01:57:08.800 --> 01:57:13.680
[Guest]: there in in such a place so i said you know five six seven people could be there these are very

01:57:13.680 --> 01:57:18.160
[Guest]: small old disused bunkers kind of places from where you know militants and or terrorists are

01:57:18.160 --> 01:57:23.520
[Guest]: sent across and these are the last stops in that in the in that sense so i said what five to seven

01:57:23.520 --> 01:57:28.160
[Guest]: people a bunker can hold a small bunker can hold an old bunker that's what that's how it would be

01:57:28.160 --> 01:57:32.240
[Guest]: and five of them have been hit so and a moment later i realized and there are those two or three

01:57:32.240 --> 01:57:36.560
[Guest]: screens which play on the in that room in the army headquarters in the south block and i realized that

01:57:36.560 --> 01:57:41.040
[Guest]: on one of these screens he's going live on mobile and he's telling that 30 to 35 people have been

01:57:41.040 --> 01:57:45.040
[Guest]: killed because five bunkers have been because five places have been hit and each of them hold

01:57:45.040 --> 01:57:50.080
[Guest]: seven people so there are 35 people and suddenly you have the headline 35 people it's actually i

01:57:50.080 --> 01:57:55.440
[Guest]: just give a mathematical answer to a very you know kind of a how do i put it a very theoretical

01:57:55.440 --> 01:58:00.640
[Guest]: question a very theoretical answer and it suddenly became inadvertently a kind of headline the 35

01:58:00.640 --> 01:58:03.680
[Guest]: and suddenly every other journalist in that room television journalists in the room started getting

01:58:03.680 --> 01:58:08.640
[Guest]: calls that you know this channel is running 35 dead why are we not running 35 dead and then they

01:58:08.640 --> 01:58:13.600
[Guest]: started running uh i think the figures whatever those figures were which eventually led to whatever

01:58:13.600 --> 01:58:18.000
[Guest]: the figures that they led to we still don't know how many actually died uh pakistan claimed two

01:58:18.000 --> 01:58:22.640
[Guest]: but i don't know whether the whether the number was uh three i think pakistan came i don't know

01:58:22.640 --> 01:58:28.720
[Guest]: whether the uh number was right or not now to the bigger question can the narrative push india and

01:58:28.720 --> 01:58:36.480
[Guest]: pakistan down a dangerous path yes i think that danger remains especially uh because the emotion

01:58:36.480 --> 01:58:41.840
[Guest]: has been whipped up to such an extent and where people genuinely believe that you know pakistan

01:58:41.840 --> 01:58:46.800
[Guest]: is something which needs to be either destroyed or annihilated or completely finished that it would

01:58:46.800 --> 01:58:51.200
[Guest]: be very difficult if something is proven or a narrative is created that something is happening

01:58:51.200 --> 01:58:57.600
[Guest]: from pakistan for india to say that it would not punish pakistan so you know you did it after

01:58:57.600 --> 01:59:03.520
[Guest]: pulwama you did it after uri and you know anything similar that happens you have raised the bar to an

01:59:03.520 --> 01:59:08.960
[Guest]: extent where you would be forced to do something to send a message and as you said if there's a

01:59:08.960 --> 01:59:13.280
[Guest]: scenario which is painted in which it is happening in a certain political context where there are

01:59:13.280 --> 01:59:20.080
[Guest]: huge political costs to inaction or to not doing uh that kind of action the choice would be a very

01:59:20.080 --> 01:59:24.640
[Guest]: tough one for the political leadership to make and it is likely that the decision would be would

01:59:24.640 --> 01:59:30.640
[Guest]: err on the bolder side and not on the side of not uh not not doing this you know if they were

01:59:30.640 --> 01:59:34.720
[Guest]: friendly relations if they were the kind of environment which you had in 2006 india probably

01:59:34.720 --> 01:59:41.600
[Guest]: got away by not doing anything after 2008 militarily except going after it diplomatically

01:59:41.600 --> 01:59:45.840
[Guest]: and putting so much of pressure on pakistan that it really squeezed pakistan very heavily

01:59:45.840 --> 01:59:51.680
[Guest]: diplomatically but did not militarily punish pakistan now the military punishment to pakistan

01:59:51.680 --> 01:59:57.600
[Guest]: these this is punitive strikes these are punitive in nature they are not essentially strikes which

01:59:57.600 --> 02:00:01.920
[Guest]: are acting as a deterrence you know that they do not deter pakistanis from not doing it again

02:00:01.920 --> 02:00:05.760
[Guest]: so you can punish them but it doesn't change their behavior you punish them with the surgical

02:00:05.760 --> 02:00:10.800
[Guest]: strikes they still pulwama happens you do balakot but the militancy does not come down in kashmir

02:00:10.800 --> 02:00:15.760
[Guest]: or the line of control does not become peaceful so a lot of people call it political theater

02:00:15.760 --> 02:00:20.400
[Guest]: meant for domestic consumption because if you're not really altering the behavior of the adversary

02:00:20.400 --> 02:00:24.400
[Guest]: then what is this about you know it's what is what is its strategic importance and i think

02:00:24.400 --> 02:00:28.640
[Guest]: that's a question which remains unanswered and that's a question which a lot of people need to

02:00:28.640 --> 02:00:33.680
[Guest]: ask as to what the value of these strikes is if they are not deterring pakistan or forcing it to

02:00:33.680 --> 02:00:39.520
[Amit Varma]: alter its behavior i mean the value is obviously domestic consumption but then the point is that

02:00:39.520 --> 02:00:43.920
[Amit Varma]: every time it's like a hit of a drug that even for domestic consumption you'll have to take it

02:00:43.920 --> 02:00:49.120
[Amit Varma]: up one notch and while you don't actually change the adversary's behavior in a positive way you

02:00:49.120 --> 02:00:53.840
[Amit Varma]: can affect it in a negative way if they then have to play to their political constituencies and

02:00:53.840 --> 02:00:59.120
[Amit Varma]: respond in some way and i guess there's always a danger of that happening my next question is about

02:00:59.120 --> 02:01:04.080
[Amit Varma]: before we get to indo china which is fascinating in itself and we'll take up some time but just to

02:01:04.080 --> 02:01:08.880
[Amit Varma]: end with uh sort of the india pakistan with the question about recent events which is that in

02:01:08.880 --> 02:01:13.120
[Amit Varma]: fact like i heard that president biden's administration made a little bit of a

02:01:13.120 --> 02:01:18.800
[Amit Varma]: difference in the way india approaches all of this in fact an insider told me a couple of days ago i

02:01:18.800 --> 02:01:23.040
[Amit Varma]: don't know how true this is maybe you'll have more information that one of the reasons that internet

02:01:23.040 --> 02:01:28.160
[Amit Varma]: was restored in kashmir was that the biden administrate station made it a precondition for

02:01:28.160 --> 02:01:32.880
[Amit Varma]: talking further to modi and equally they've kind of said that listen you really have to chill on

02:01:32.880 --> 02:01:37.840
[Amit Varma]: all this anti-pakistan rhetoric and all of that which is why in these current elections you don't

02:01:37.840 --> 02:01:42.880
[Amit Varma]: have so much anti-pakistan talk or almost any anti-pakistan talk coming from the bjp because

02:01:42.880 --> 02:01:50.320
[Amit Varma]: they are kind of now uh chilling so how big a role is um sort of the u.s approach uh to this

02:01:50.320 --> 02:01:55.440
[Guest]: whole situation yeah amit just coming before this question let me let me just rewind to the

02:01:55.440 --> 02:01:59.600
[Guest]: statement you made at the back at the beginning of the question about the narrative and the

02:01:59.600 --> 02:02:04.880
[Guest]: political calculations that can lead to pakistani response so what has happened so far in the two

02:02:04.880 --> 02:02:11.120
[Guest]: instances the surgical strikes and the balakot strikes how the pakistanis have dealt with it is

02:02:11.120 --> 02:02:14.880
[Guest]: they completely denied the surgical strikes they said nothing happened so they didn't need to

02:02:14.880 --> 02:02:20.000
[Guest]: respond the narrative from their side was on the when it have came to balakot they said that the

02:02:20.000 --> 02:02:25.040
[Guest]: balakot air strikes did not hit the target did not lead to any casualties so you know it was really

02:02:25.040 --> 02:02:29.440
[Guest]: an effective strike and then they came back and did whatever little bit they did on the indian

02:02:29.440 --> 02:02:35.760
[Guest]: side of the line of control so in that sense they also found a way to address their own political

02:02:35.760 --> 02:02:42.320
[Guest]: constituency without really climbing up the escalation ladder now that's pretty lucky on

02:02:42.320 --> 02:02:46.800
[Guest]: on the part of both countries it may or may not happen every single time and i think that's where

02:02:46.800 --> 02:02:52.000
[Guest]: the fear that you raise really comes into play things can quickly go out of hand in such a

02:02:52.000 --> 02:02:57.280
[Guest]: scenario you know just to give a counterfactual if the indian fighter pilot had died in pakistan

02:02:57.280 --> 02:03:03.040
[Guest]: army custody after balakot the indian response would have been completely different and pakistan

02:03:03.040 --> 02:03:09.280
[Guest]: would have no no kind of you know uh easy card on their in their pocket to hand over to india

02:03:09.280 --> 02:03:14.000
[Guest]: the fact that pakistanis imran went to prime minister imran khan went to pakistani parliament

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:17.920
[Guest]: announced that they were handing over led to the defuse the crisis in a big way let's say if the

02:03:17.920 --> 02:03:22.240
[Guest]: if the indian fighter pilot had been had died in pakistani custody for whatever reason whether he

02:03:22.240 --> 02:03:26.240
[Guest]: was hit you know whether he was injured during the flight or whether he was beaten up by these

02:03:26.240 --> 02:03:30.480
[Guest]: by the civilians villagers when he was captured or whether he was beaten by the pakistani military

02:03:30.480 --> 02:03:35.440
[Guest]: when he was captured think of the whole situation how it would have developed pakistanis would have

02:03:35.440 --> 02:03:40.160
[Guest]: had no way in which they would have defused the crisis the emotions and the tempers in india were

02:03:40.160 --> 02:03:45.440
[Guest]: running so high that it would have been not it would not have been possible for anyone to advocate

02:03:45.440 --> 02:03:51.120
[Guest]: that let's not go and do something more with pakistan so it is those kind of situations

02:03:51.120 --> 02:03:57.280
[Guest]: accidentally otherwise which can really lead to a crisis completely going out of hand especially as

02:03:57.280 --> 02:04:01.280
[Guest]: you said with two countries which are armed with nuclear weapons uh getting back to your other

02:04:01.280 --> 02:04:06.000
[Guest]: question about the biden administration's role very clearly the kashmir internet thing whether

02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:10.480
[Guest]: it is true or not the fact is that the state department did welcome it in a very enthusiastic

02:04:10.480 --> 02:04:15.680
[Guest]: manner the date was done which was clearly a signal for a lot of things the fact that the

02:04:16.240 --> 02:04:22.160
[Guest]: that the u.s defense secretary not general mattis but not general austin but secretary austin when

02:04:22.160 --> 02:04:26.240
[Guest]: he came to india the fact that he chose to go public in the press conference and say that he

02:04:26.240 --> 02:04:31.840
[Guest]: had spoken to india about the backsliding of democracy and various democratic freedoms

02:04:31.840 --> 02:04:37.040
[Guest]: clearly indicates that it wanted to send a message to the indian side this democratic party the

02:04:37.040 --> 02:04:42.800
[Guest]: current democratic party amit as you know has a lot of people who are far left on the progressive

02:04:42.800 --> 02:04:48.240
[Guest]: side than historically the democratic party has been and this administration particularly

02:04:48.240 --> 02:04:53.120
[Guest]: has been speaking tough on many issues with many other countries and if india has to stand

02:04:53.120 --> 02:04:59.200
[Guest]: uh in contrast to china particularly on the issue of democracy and liberal values then i think there

02:04:59.200 --> 02:05:05.200
[Guest]: would be pressure on india whether said or unsaid to deal with those issues it's not something india

02:05:05.200 --> 02:05:10.400
[Guest]: can get away lightly with because of china uh it's something that would come into focus even

02:05:10.400 --> 02:05:17.280
[Guest]: if it's not spoken publicly or spoken semi-publicly as secretary austin did it definitely plays and

02:05:17.280 --> 02:05:22.560
[Guest]: will continue to play a part in the india u.s relations going forward let's talk about

02:05:22.560 --> 02:05:28.720
[Amit Varma]: talk about china now because china suddenly kind of burst onto the consciousness in the

02:05:28.720 --> 02:05:34.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of adversarial framework as it were in the last few years you know we lost the 62 war and

02:05:34.720 --> 02:05:39.280
[Amit Varma]: that kind of happened and then for decades it's almost like there's been nothing there have been

02:05:39.280 --> 02:05:44.080
[Amit Varma]: these little outstanding disputes but there's kind of been no action it's almost as if we are too

02:05:44.080 --> 02:05:49.360
[Amit Varma]: small for china to bother with and when we start becoming big you could argue we start becoming

02:05:49.360 --> 02:05:56.000
[Amit Varma]: big as a market as well where their manufacturers can sell stuff so you know why would they create a

02:05:56.000 --> 02:06:01.200
[Amit Varma]: conflict or go for conflict and all of that and equally the situation is like you pointed out that

02:06:01.200 --> 02:06:05.120
[Amit Varma]: if there was a hypothetical war in a thought experiment with china we would of course not

02:06:05.120 --> 02:06:10.320
[Amit Varma]: stand a chance and they know that and we know that so beyond the point is really not much we can do

02:06:10.320 --> 02:06:14.640
[Amit Varma]: that's my layman's understanding of it obviously there are nuances to it and you'll correct me

02:06:14.640 --> 02:06:19.840
[Amit Varma]: so tell me a little bit about what's brewing here what are china's motivations what is a

02:06:19.840 --> 02:06:25.120
[Amit Varma]: predicament that india finds itself in where for example we can't even admit that we've lost some

02:06:25.120 --> 02:06:29.920
[Amit Varma]: territory for domestic political reasons obviously you know and in the middle of all this like all

02:06:29.920 --> 02:06:35.760
[Amit Varma]: india could do was ban poetic talk which i loved which is like really sad but and which empowered

02:06:35.760 --> 02:06:40.800
[Amit Varma]: many people in uh you know small town india and rural india who didn't have any other platform

02:06:40.800 --> 02:06:45.040
[Amit Varma]: that spoke to them so it's just tragic at a at multiple levels i just feel horrible about that

02:06:45.040 --> 02:06:52.160
[Guest]: but what's happening just enlighten us so essentially there is a line which goes directly

02:06:52.160 --> 02:06:59.680
[Guest]: the chinese behavior changes around 2012 2013 with respect to india whether they believe that

02:06:59.680 --> 02:07:03.360
[Guest]: they were coming on to their own whether they believe that india was getting too closely

02:07:03.360 --> 02:07:07.440
[Guest]: aligned to the us whether they believe the time had come when the existing arrangements between

02:07:07.440 --> 02:07:13.280
[Guest]: india and china which had held good for some 20 odd years had no longer held good the behavior

02:07:13.280 --> 02:07:17.280
[Guest]: changes around that time and this is all the officials who dealt with china at that point in

02:07:17.280 --> 02:07:21.840
[Guest]: time have now in hindsight said that this is the time when things start changing with changing with

02:07:21.840 --> 02:07:27.120
[Guest]: china china's behavior becomes more assertive more aggressive it starts pushing more it has

02:07:27.120 --> 02:07:33.040
[Guest]: better infrastructure better economy and everything else the major turning point comes in doklam in

02:07:33.040 --> 02:07:39.680
